<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Consumer Prices Up by 0.1 Percent in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. consumer prices, helped
by a record decline in natural gas costs, increased by 0.1 percent
in March, the U.S. Labor Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The tiny rise in the Consumer Price Index was substantially
below the 0.3 percent advance in February.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the cost of gasoline, home heating oil and
natural gas all declined in March. The 4.2 percent drop in natural
gas prices was the biggest one-month decline since the government
began keeping records in 1952.
</P>
<P>
Total energy costs in the U.S. declined by 1.7 percent in the
month, the biggest decrease since a 2 percent decline last June.
</P>
<P>
Food costs were unchanged in March after having jumped 0.3
percent in February.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile energy and food categories, the
so-called core rate of inflation posted a modest 0.2 percent
increase in March, matching the February gain.
</P>
<P>
For the first three months of this year, U.S. consumer prices
were rising at an annual rate of just 1.8 percent, far below the
3.3 percent increase for all of 1996. The improvement reflected
moderation in both food and energy costs, which had been adding to
price pressures most of last year.
</P>
<P>
The core inflation rate in the past three months has been
rising at an annual rate of 2.6 percent, only slightly higher than
the 2.4 percent for all of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Many analysts say the U.S. economic expansion is too rapid and
the resulting wage and price pressures will trigger higher
inflation unless the U.S. Federal Reserve dampens demand by
increasing borrowing costs. It seems that the report could relieve
some economists' worries on the inflation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
