<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French PM Vows to Ban Illegal Telephone Tapping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 15 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Alain Juppe
today told the French National Assembly (lower house of
parliament) that he would "put an end to the totally condemnable
practice of " illegal phone tappings in France.
</P>
<P>
"I intend to put an end with your help to the totally
condemnable practices which jeopardize the individual liberty and
private life of the persons," said Juppe.
</P>
<P>
He said that "if necessary," he would "go further to change
the legislation" on tapping operations by government bodies.
</P>
<P>
Juppe last week ordered the re-examination of the tapping
operation launched by an anti-terrorist cellular under former
President Francois Mitterrand from 1983 to 1986, after the
National Committee of Control on Interception of Secrets accused
the former president of abusing the operation for private
purposes.
</P>
<P>
The commission said that 100,000 French citizens have become
the victim of illegal telephone tapping by government bodies and
private individuals who wanted to collect industrial and social
information, or out of suspicion or curiosity.
</P>
<P>
The commission's chairman, Paul Bouchet, said that he would
lift the defense on the secret of some of the tappings in order to
fully publicize the scandal.
</P>
<P>
But Juppe said that it is the responsibility of the government
and the state to protect individuals and groups in "the
collective interests and security of the nation" through defense
of secret.
</P>
<P>
"No one could decide to lift the defense of secret... because
this will not find its justification except in the superior
interests of the state," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
