<HEADLINE> UK Rejects EU Deal on Reducing Fishing Quotas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The British government has flatly
rejected a European Union (EU) agreement on reducing fishing
quotas by saying that it has "not a shred of intention" of
implementing the deal.
</P>
<P>
The EU fisheries ministers meeting in Luxembourg voted today to
slash EU fishing quotas by 30 percent through reduced trawlers
fleets in a bid to conserve the most depleted fish stocks.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters today in Tavistock of western England,
British Prime Minister John Major said that the British government
would ignore the EU decision until an agreement with EU partners
was reached on quota-hopping, which means Spanish and Dutch
fishermen grab British share of fishing quotas by buying British
fishing licences.
</P>
<P>
"I have not a shred of intention of cutting the British catch
until or unless we get a satisfactory agreement on quota-hopping."
</P>
<P>
Major also reaffirmed his determination of blocking the EU's
Inter-Governmental Conference (IGC) at the EU Summit to be held in
Amsterdam in June unless the quota-hopping issue was resolved.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British Fisheries Minister Tony Baldry echoed
Major's tough words by telling his EU counterparts in Luxembourg
"the UK isn't prepared to contemplate any further reduction in its
fishing fleet until the whole issue of quota-hoppers is dealt
with."
</P>
<P>
"That's grossly unfair on British fishermen and can not
continue," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
