<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden to Spend 2 Billion Dollars to Cut Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Swedish Finance Minister Eric
Asbrink earmarked 16.3 billion kronor (2.1 billion U.S. dollars)
in his spring budget plan unveiled today to slash the country's
unemployment rate from 10 to 4.5 percent by 2000.
</P>
<P>
The plan, presented to parliament for approval, includes
proposals to fund early retirement schemes, reduce social charges
for small businesses and encouraging local governments to put the
jobless back to work.
</P>
<P>
The target jobless rate of 4.5 percent falls short of the
government's aim of keeping unemployment below 4 percent by the
end of the century. The government has made tackling unemployment
one of its overriding priorities.
</P>
<P>
A report from the Swedish Labor Market Board last week said
there are 334,626 people out of work, about 10 percent of the
country's labor force.
</P>
<P>
In his budget plan, the finance minister forecast gross
domestic product (GDP) would grow 2.3 percent this year and 2.5
percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
He also targeted the budget deficit to be 2.1 percent of GDP,
well below the 3 percent criteria set out in the Maastricht Treaty
for European Union countries wanting to join the single currency
in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
