<HEADLINE> Russia, U.S. Still at Odds Over NATO's Expansion: Yeltsin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said today that the U.S.-Russia summit in Helsinki last month
didn't eliminate the differences between the two countries on
NATO's eastward expansion plans, the media reported.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who will begin a three-day visit to Germany tomorrow,
was speaking in an interview with German reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said he told President Bill Clinton at the summit that it
was a mistake for NATO to invite former Soviet bloc countries to
join the alliance.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said that Russia and the U.S. agreed at the summit that
NATO would not deploy nuclear weapons or additional troops
on the territories of new members. Russia will also sign accords
with all NATO members about their relations with Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
