<HEADLINE> UK Retail Sale Price Rises Slow down in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The rate of retail sale price
rises in Britain declined last month due to the combined effect of
tough competition among retailers and a strong pound, according to
the British Retail Consortium (BRC) today.
</P>
<P>
The annual value of retail sales in March rose 3.7 percent,
down from 4.3 percent in February and 4.9 percent in January,
reflecting "continuing downward pressure on prices", the BRC said.
</P>
<P>
The figures showed how low inflation was in the retail sector,
although some sectors had been hit by uncertainty in the general
election run-up, the BRC added.
</P>
<P>
The BRC figures followed Monday's official statistics showing a
fall in manufacturers' input and output prices in March.
</P>
<P>
The combination triggered economists' speculation that an
expected half-point rise in base interest rates after the general
election next month may be averted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
