<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guinea Bissau to Join African Franc Zone in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Guinea Bissau will replace its
non-convertible currency of peso with African franc on May 4, to
become the first Portuguese-speaking African nation to join the
African franc zone, the Agence France-Presse reported today.
</P>
<P>
Guinea Bissau will sign its adhesion to the franc zone at the
conference of finance ministers of the franc zone countries to be
held in the Cotonou, the capital of Benin, on April 16-17.
</P>
<P>
Two English speaking African countries, Gambia and Ghana, and
Guinea-Conakry, could also join the 14-nation franc zone, in which
the CFA franc is convertible with the French franc with a fixed
rate of 100 CFA francs for one French franc.
</P>
<P>
The admission of Guinea Bissau by the franc zone is backed by
the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank, which estimate
that the CFA franc has recovered from an overnight 50 percent
devaluation against the French franc by the French central bank on
January 1, 1994.
</P>
<P>
All the countries in the African franc zone have registered a 5
percent annual economic growth since 1995, and officials of the
French Ministry of Finance have expressed confidence over the
stability of the parity between the CFA franc and the French
franc.
</P>
<P>
The devaluation of CFA franc caused an earthquake in the cities
of the franc zone countries, while their rural areas benefited
from the devaluation which stimulated export of farm products.
</P>
<P>
The franc zone member countries are Benin, Burkina Faso,
Cameroon, the Central African Republic, the Comoros, Cote
d'Ivoire, Gabon, Guinea Equatorial, Mali, Niger, Senegal, Chad and
Togo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
