<HEADLINE> S.Korean Speaker to Be Questioned Over Hanbo Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 15 (Xinhua) -- South Korean prosecutors said today
that they would summon National Assembly Speaker Kim Soo-han for
questioning this week over allegations he received money from
the owner of the failed Hanbo business group.
</P>
<P>
Kim, one of 33 persons alleged to be on the bribery list of
Hanbo's owner Chung Tae-soo, is suspected of having received 50
million won (about 560,000 U.S. dollars) in political donations
from Hanbo, whose flagship unit Hanbo Steel Co. collapsed in January
under six billion dollars of debt.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutor's action came right after the Seoul Conference
of the Inter-Parliamentary Union, which Kim chairs, closed this
morning after a six-day session.
</P>
<P>
Kim, the highest level political figure publicly named for his
involvement in the Hanbo bribes-for-loans scandal, refused to
appear at the prosecutor's office for questioning, citing his
position as head of the legislature, an official said.
</P>
<P>
One of Kim's aides said prosecutors were going too far in
calling in the head of the legislative body without any concrete
evidence.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors said that they would complete the questioning
within this week and that Kim could be questioned at a venue of
his choice rather than at the Prosecutor's office.
</P>
<P>
This latest move by prosecutors to spread the investigation
into the scandal to ruling and opposition presidential hopefuls
and powerful parliamentary figures, is embarrassing the
Presidential Office Chongwadae.
</P>
<P>
A top offical accused the prosecution of intentionally leaking
news of the Speaker's summoning to the press despite the
presidential office's wish for the prosecution to deal with the
matter carefully to protect Kim's image.
</P>
<P>
Lee Hoi-chang, the second executive after President Kim Young
-sam of the ruling New Korea Party (NKP), accused the prosecution
of investigating politicians indiscriminately.
</P>
<P>
He warned that summoning politicians and officials allegedly on
Chung Tae-soo's list was destroying the political status of the
nation and called for an early end to the investigations.
</P>
<P>
Forty-one people involved in the scandal, including Chung and
his aides, his son Chung Bo-keun and several officials and
lawmakers, have been arrested since the scandal broke in January.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution decided last week to summon the 33 officials
and lawmakers on the so-called Chung bribery list. They are
alleged to have helped Chung to obtain 5 trillion won in loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
