<HEADLINE> Euro-Med Conference Opens in Malta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VALLETTA, MALTA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Ministers from the 15
European Union (EU) members and their 12 Mediterranean partners
today started their two-day discussions on how to advance their
ambitious cooperation process.
</P>
<P>
The Malta conference, the second of this type, is expected to
review the progress achieved in the Euro-Mediterranean cooperation
which was launched in the first Barcelona conference in November
1995, and find practical ways to push it ahead.
</P>
<P>
The Barcelona conference set up a goal to establish an EU-Med
free-trade zone by 2010 through forging partnership with Algeria,
Cyprus, Egypt, Israel, Jordan, Lebanon, Malta, Morocco, Syria,
Tunisia, Turkey and Palestine.
</P>
<P>
Also on the agenda is the faltering Middle East peace process
which has caused severe tension between Israel and Arab countries.
Analysts voiced fear that the issue could cast shadow over the
dialogue on economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In protest against Israeli hard-line policy in the Middle East
process, the Arab League announced a fortnight ago the suspension
of normalization of relations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
But Hans Van Mierlo, who toured the southern Mediterranean
countries before the meeting, has said the Middle East will be
discussed, but "very moderately."
</P>
<P>
The participation of all the partners, including the presence
of Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat and
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy, at the Malta conference
itself is fruitful, EU officials and European Commission
Vice-President Manuel Marin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
