<HEADLINE> Pakistan PM Urges Closer Ties With C. Asian States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif today vowed to pursue an independent foreign policy
supported by a strong defense capability and a vibrant economy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the National Defense College here, Sharif said
Pakistan was keen to have meaningful economic cooperation with
Central Asian states.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, which enjoys cultural and religious affinity with
these states, is eager to strengthen its ties with them in all
fields, said Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan offered the shortest route for international trade
with Central Asian States, he noted.
</P>
<P>
On Afghanistan, The Prime Minister said Pakistan would continue
to support the efforts by the United Nations and the Organization
of the Islamic Conference for restoration of peace and
reconciliation there.
</P>
<P>
"We have faith in the wisdom of the Afghan people. They would
not accept any solution imposed on them from abroad," he said.
</P>
<P>
Talking about Pakistan's ties with the United States and other
countries, he said, Pakistan attaches great importance to its
relationship with the United States, and the European Union and
Japan for political, economic and commercial and technological
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Russia, he said, remained an important world power with a
traditional relationship with India and strong links with as well
as military presence in the Central Asian states.
</P>
<P>
"Our basic objective is to work towards improving relations
with Russia so that it moves to a more even-handed approach in its
policy in South Asia," the Prime Minister said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
