<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BT's Merger with MCI Pays Way for "Attack" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- British Telecommunications Plc's
(BT) shareholders overwhelmingly voted on Tuesday in favor of the
merger with US group MCI Communications Corp which would create
one of the first great companies of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Addressing shareholders at the Extraordinary General Meeting
here this afternoon, BT's Chairman Iain Vallance said: "If BT is
to develop and grow, it will do so most successfully with MCI, in
Concert."
</P>
<P>
"Together we can bring benefits to our customers and
shareholders that we simply could not deliver alone," he added.
</P>
<P>
The global telecommunications market is huge -- more than 650
billion US dollars today, and expected to top a trillion dollars
by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
At the moment BT and MCI have a six percent share of that
global market, but outside the US and the UK only 17 percent of
the market is open to competition; by the year 2000 that could be
95 percent.
</P>
<P>
Vallance said: "There is a great opportunity here. Were we to
do nothing more than to hold on to that six percent, Concert would
have revenues of 34 billion pounds (54.4 billion US dollars)
within a few years."
</P>
<P>
BT officials claimed that with MCI at its side, they can stride
together to conquer new markets.
</P>
<P>
BT and its new partner MCI on Monday beat AT&AMP;T, America's
biggest long-distance operator, by signing up Portugal Telecom to
help gain a backdoor route into the South American market.
</P>
<P>
The deal involves the two companies investing 113 million US
dollars for a 1.5pc stake in the next stage of Portugal Telecom's
privatization later in the year.
</P>
<P>
The latest expansion is seen as well-timed and likely to
reinforce BT's contention that buying MCI is the only way to
provide a genuinely global service to customers.
</P>
<P>
However, some analysts continue to have reservations about the
price BT is paying and the potential commercial benefits.
</P>
<P>
A strategy, announced for the mergered company, is "not tilting
at windmills but a focused plan of attack".
</P>
<P>
The primary focus would be on Europe and on the US local
markets which offered a new 100 billion US dollars opportunity.
There is also a need to build the company's presence in Asia
Pacific and in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
The deal still needs approval from the European Commission and
the US Federal Communications Commission (FCC).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
