<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Introduces Facility to Promote Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Industrial Development Bank
(IDB) of Kenya has negotiated some export and import financing
facilities to develop Kenyan industries.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper Kenya Times today quoted the IDB Group's
chief of operations J.G. Chege as saying that the trade financing
facility would facilitate the import of industrial inputs and
stimulate exports of Kenyan goods.
</P>
<P>
The bank official said that the IDB had negotiated a credit
line with the Export/Import Bank of India worth 5 million U.S.
Dollars to finance the import of capital goods from India.
</P>
<P>
He noted that it also had successful negotiations with the
China Export/Import Bank, which would finance finished and
capital goods from China with the trade credit line amounting to
10 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The bank has also entered a credit line with the Africa
Export/Import Bank, a subsidiary of the African Development Bank
based in Cairo, Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Chege pointed out that the financing facility amounting to a
loan of 5 million Dollars would facilitate the import and export
of goods between Africa and Europe.
</P>
<P>
A credit facility of 3 million Dollars with the Export/Import
Bank of Korea will not only finance trade between the two
countries, but also serve as an important link between Kenya and
one of the emerging Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Chege noted that the introduction of all these trade financing
facilities is designed to spur Kenya's industrial expansion and
create employment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
