<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Rebels Surrender to Government Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Dozens of former Sierra Leonean
rebels surrendered to government forces in the north of the
country in the past three days, reports reaching here today said.
</P>
<P>
The report said in the town of Magbunaka, over 100 rebels
surrendered on Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
''They (rebels ) are haggard looking, malnourished and had
advanced stages of skin diseases'', an official of the Sierra
Leone Red Cross said in a telephone interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
She quoted one of the rebels as saying ''we had
only taken the risk to give ourselves up as we were told by our
colleagues we would be shot by government troops''.
</P>
<P>
West African diplomats said the security situation in the
west African state has ''improved'' despite fears that the
leadership struggle within the Revolutionary United Front
(RUF) ''would adversely affect progress towards the restoration of
peace''.
</P>
<P>
A Defence Ministry official told Xinhua that since March 5
when the leadership struggle emerged, ''incidents of ceasefire
violations and ambushes have in fact drastically reduced''.
</P>
<P>
''Everything is calm'', she added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the military said the rebels are now operating in
three areas in the country, namely Kailahun in the far east,
Kangari Hills in the north and Bradford in the south.
enditem

=04151729
NNNN
01:27 01:27 g # PAB
