<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Extends Vocational Training for Interns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The South African Interim
Medical and Dental Council (SAIMDC) has approved two years of
additional vocational training for medical practitioners as of
1998, extending doctors' training from seven to nine years.
</P>
<P>
Under the SAIMDC decision, doctors doing their internship this
year would have to do an additional two-year training before they
are allowed to enter private practice, the South African Press
Association (SAPA) quoted SAIMDC registrar Nico Prinsloo as
reporting today.
</P>
<P>
In the past, graduates only did one year's vocational training
before entering the field.
</P>
<P>
Prinsloo said the vocational training would be done at
institutions recognized by the council, saying that they would
have to meet certain requirements, such as the availability of
facilities and supervisors.
</P>
<P>
Provision for the introduction of the system would be included
as part of the council's recommendations relating to amendments
to the Medical Act, which are expected to be tabled in parliament
this year, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
