<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan PM on Strong Defense, Vibrant Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif today vowed to pursue an independent foreign policy
supported by a strong defense capability and a vibrant economy and
said the economic center of gravity is shifting to the
Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the National Defense College here, Sharif said his
priorities for the future of Pakistan will be to achieve a strong
and impregnable defense capability and pursue an independent
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
To revive the national economy and strengthen the industrial
and agricultural sectors will also be on the top agenda of the
government, said Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said his government will also launch a crash program for
the development of infrastructure and make great efforts for
restoration of law and order and creation of a sense of security
among the people.
</P>
<P>
He also said the government will restructure financial
institutions to safeguard national resources, and pledged to
continue the accountability process and eradicate corruption.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need to strengthen Pakistan's infrastructure
and said it was important for Pakistan to develop its trade and
commercial ties with Central Asian states.
</P>
<P>
The great hub of commercial and industrial activities in the
Central Asian region will help uplift not only Pakistan's economy
but also that of the entire region, said Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said he was seeking to revive Pakistan's economy through
bold innovative measures. "We are taking difficult but
well-thought-out decisions. These decisions were long overdue and
necessary," said the Prime Minister.
</P>
<P>
He noted that his government had introduced revolutionary
reforms in the taxation system, reducing taxes and expanding the
revenue base.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, with a relatively strong record of economic growth of
over six percent, had been driven during the last three years into
recession marked by runaway inflation, high unemployment and an
unbearable burden of debt, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said his government will work in concert with people from
all walks of life to bring about a just social order, "which can
be achieved only with unity of purpose and a demonstration of our
ability to shape our destiny."  
</P>
</TEXT>
