<HEADLINE> Rampant Catch Threatens Fish in Western Ugandan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Rampant catch of immature fish
is threatening existence of the fish resources in lakes George
and Edward in western Uganda, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Dangerous situation will face future generations of fish if no
stern measures be taken to curb the trend, said Bamusede
Bwambale, a local official from western Kasese District, quoted
by "The New Vision".
</P>
<P>
Kana Mbaga, a local fishery assistant, said the curbing of
illegal fishing is the responsibility of Zonal Fishery Office,
but an official in the office said they did not patrol the lakes
ten years ago due to lack of fund.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Mbuse, assistant resident district commissioner of
Kasese District, threatened to arrest fish mongers who sell
immature fish.
</P>
<P>
Local fishermen, in their turn, complained that the government
had relaxed efforts to demobilize illegal canoes and undersized
nets on the lakes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
