<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Terrorists Attempted Pope's Life, Bosnian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The explosives discovered last
weekend along the route taken by visiting Pope John Paul II were
the work of international terrorists, a senior Bosnian official
said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mehmed Zilic, interior minister of the Bosnian (Muslim-Croat)
Federation, revealed this finding at a press conference here, but
he did not specify which international terrorist group was behind
the incident.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, 23 anti-tank mines and plastic explosives attached
to a remote control device were found under a bridge the motorcade
of the Pope would pass just hours before he landed in Sarajevo
airport.
</P>
<P>
Zilic said that the explosives were enough to blow up the
bridge and kill people within a range of a hundred meters.
</P>
<P>
The interior minister said that no suspects had been arrested
so far and denied reports in Italian media that four Turkish
nationals were detained in connection with the incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
