<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Sees Heavier Task for African Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 15 (Xinhua) -- African countries are facing heavier
tasks to handle although many of them have made tremedous progress
since independence in the 1960s, a United Nations Development Program
(UNDP) official said today.
</P>
<P>
Babashola Chinsman, UNDP Resident Representative in Nigeria, noted
that many African countries in the past four decades made spirited
efforts to improve the well being of their citizens in a broad range
of social, economic, institutional and policy reforms.
</P>
<P>
However, "the task facing Africa today is heavier than ever before
and the challenges of extreme poverty, social injustice, social
exclusion, marginalization and environmental degradation are many and
daunting," he said, quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The age-long development approach of economic growth and top-down
planning had not improved the people's welfare, he said, stressing that
the current development strategy and efforts need to be oriented to
the people.
</P>
<P>
At a three-day workshop on "sustainable human development" organized
by the UNDP today in Kaduna, northern Nigeria, Chinsman said the vogue
now was to evolve policies that promote the private sector as the
engine of growth and good governance.
</P>
<P>
The policies should also ensure sustainable unilization of a
nation's natural resources to promote development, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
