<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Calls for European Role in Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VALLETTA, MALTA, April 15 (Xinhua)--Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat today called for Europe's
role in realizing stability in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
He made the appeal at the opening ceremony of the two-day
European-Mediterranean conference here, which was attended by
ministers from the 15 European Union(EU) members and their 12
southern Mediterranean partners.
</P>
<P>
Arafat expressed his appreciation for European support to the
Palestinians in the Middle East peace process, describing as close
the Euro-Palestinian relationship.
</P>
<P>
He said the Israeli settlement policy, particularly the Har
Homa plan in East Jerusalem, has constituted a serious violation
of the signed agreements in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The issue of the faltering Middle East process has drawn much
attention at the Malta Euro-Med conference, the second to the
Barcelona held in November 1995. There is a general concern that
the issue would cast shadow on the economic cooperation topics at
the conference.
</P>
<P>
A Number of delegations, particularly those from EU members,
called for concentration on common interests among the partners,
instead of hurling accusations upon each other over their
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
But still, political and security issues are being much talked
about in conference, which is designed to deal with issues on
cooperation in various dimensions.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said the Palestinian people lay much emphasis on the
political and security dimension, viewing it as a prerequisite for
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians' cooperation with Israel is based on the
implementation of all the signed peace agreements, he said, adding
a lack of Israel-Palestinian cooperation has made the Palestinian
people in self-control areas suffer a lot.
</P>
<P>
The Malta meeting is aimed at paving way for the
Euro-Mediterranean cooperation which has a goal of establishing a
free trade zone involving the EU and its 12 Mediterranean partners,
namely Algeria, Cyprus, Egypt, Israel, Jordan, Lebanon,Malta,
Morocco,Syria,Tunisia, Turkey and Palestine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
