<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More U.S. Cargo Handled by Canadian Ports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- More and more cargo destined for
the United States is being routed through Canadian ports as a
result of lower taxes and deeper harbors, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
A new study shows that the value of U.S. cargo shipments
handled by Canadian ports jumped 15 percent in 1995 to nearly 20
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The study found that the value of U.S. exports shipped through
Canada in 1995 rose 13.4 percent to 7.72 billion dollars, while
the value of U.S. imports rose 17.1 percent to 12.04 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Most of these shipments originated in or are destined for
Europe, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. shippers use more Canadian ports for several reasons. One
is that silting has left U.S. ports shallower than Canadian ones,
experts said.
</P>
<P>
Another is the U.S. harbor maintenance tax, which can add
hundreds of dollars to the costs of a container shipment. Since
the tax was quadrupled in the past six years, there has been a
sharp increase in diversions.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the tax is tied to the value of goods shipped,
which means high-priced goods such as computers and machinery tend
to be routed through Canada, the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
