<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Gov't, Opposition Fail to Reach Compromise on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the German ruling
coalition and the main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD)
today failed to strike a compromise on a government plan to
overhaul the country's taxation system, but agreed to continue
negotiations later this month.
</P>
<P>
After more than three-hour of talks with German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl, SPD leader Oskar Lafontaine said that the tax reform
package put forward by the government was still unacceptable. But
he also declared that the high-level negotiations will continue.
</P>
<P>
According to Finance Minister Theo Waigel, the next
Kohl-Lafontaine tax summit would be on April 23.
</P>
<P>
Kohl said after the meeting that he would "try everything in
order to bring (the tax talks) to a result". The tax reform was
urgently needed in order to boost the economy and create new jobs,
he added.
</P>
<P>
But he declined to predict whether an agreement with the
opposition was possible.
</P>
<P>
Both Kohl and Waigel said that the government would soon bring
its package before the lower house of the parliament known as the
Bundestag, parallel to the negotiations with the SPD. According to
them, the first parliament reading of the government package could
begin as early as mid next week.
</P>
<P>
Aimed at bolstering business confidence, investment and hiring,
tax reform has become the German government's top domestic policy
priority and its main recipe to curb unemployment, which is
currently at a post-war record high of about 4.5 million.
</P>
<P>
Under its proposed reform plan, the government wants, among
other things, to cut income taxes to 15 percent for low-wage
earners and 39 percent for people with high incomes instead of the
current marginal rates ranging from 25.9 percent to 53 percent.
</P>
<P>
If succeeded, it would be the country's biggest tax-revision
package since 1949.
</P>
<P>
The SPD, however, has spoken in favor of keeping the top income
rate at 53 percent or trimming it only modestly, a strategy meant
to keep the tax burden on those best suited to pay.
</P>
<P>
The government needs to strike a compromise with the SPD if the
reform plan is to survive the upper house of the German
parliament, Bundesrat, where the SPD controls a majority.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said government and opposition still had a long way to
go before reaching a compromise, but they remained confident that
an agreement would be possible within this year.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have held two previous rounds of negotiations
since February 26, both failed to make headway. The SPD walked out
of the talks last month to show solidarity with coal miners
protesting against a government plan to cut state subsidies for
the inefficient coal-mining industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
