<HEADLINE> Mandela Calls Mutual Trust in Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 15 (Xinhua) -- South Africa could not
succeed unless there was maximum cooperation between
democratically-elected officials and employees in the public
service, President Nelson Mandela said today.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's remarks, made in his state-of-the-nation address
introducing debate on his budget in the National Assembly in Cape
Town, was apparently referring to a public row between National
Police Commissioner George Fivaz and Safety and Security Minister
Sydney Mufamadi, reported the South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said the new constitution was clear on the issues of
political authority and operation autonomy, adding mutual
confidence deriving from integrity and mutual trust in pursuit of
common objectives should always be cherished.
</P>
<P>
Success would elude South Africa if capacity problems in the
civil service, the criminal justice system, the provinces and
local authorities, and the economy had not been addressed,
frankly and urgently, said the President.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the level of crime would not come down just because
the resources available to the criminal justice system had been
boosted, if the responsible agencies did not have operation and
managerial skills and the communities did not accept their
responsibility to join the police in fighting crime, he added.
</P>
<P>
Fivaz was allegedly threatening to resign unless he was assured by
Mandela there would be no political interference in his job.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Mufamadi was also reportedly accusing Fivaz of
having broken an agreement about how the restructuring of the
police would be announced.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Mandela endorsed Mufamadi and Fivaz as the best
team "the country ever has to ensure the citizens of South Africa
have safety and security". 
</P>
</TEXT>
