<HEADLINE> British PM Urges End to EU Beef Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister John Major once
again urged today the European Union to lift its ban on British
beef exports which started following the mad cow crisis in March
of last year.
</P>
<P>
Major said EU's beef ban should be ended now that Britain was
slaughtering cattle most at risk of carrying the disease and had
tightened its hygiene checks on meat, which were now the toughest
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, speaking to farmers at the market town of
Tavistock in western England in his campaign tour, said the
crisis, which has so far cost British taxpayers 3.5 billion pounds
(5.7 billion U.S. dollars), was not the fault of farmers but "the
result of market panic and in some cases political panic in
countries right the way across Europe."
</P>
<P>
The mad cow crisis erupted in March 1996 when the European
Union slapped a worldwide ban on British beef after scientists
discovered evidence that a fatal brain-wasting disease could be
transmitted to humans from cattle.
</P>
<P>
He told the European partners that Britain has put its house
neatly in order and they should follow suit.
</P>
<P>
"So firstly, begin to lift the ban on British beef and,
secondly, since you have felt so strongly about us putting our
house in order, isn't it about time that you put your own house in
order?" Major said.
</P>
<P>
Major toughened his position on Europe policies these days
partly to woo voters by staunchly defending the national interest.
The ruling Conservative Party still lags behind the opposition
Labor Party but the gap has been narrowed from last week's 23
percentage points to the current 16 points in Sunday's opinion
polls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
