<HEADLINE> Report Faults FBI Lab on Some Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. Justice Department
report said on Tuesday some of the FBI crime lab's practices need
"substantial change."
</P>
<P>
The report by the department's inspector general stems from an
18-month investigation following Dr. Frederic Whitehurst's charges
that tests in the FBI forensic lab were routinely skewed in favor
of the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
A number of cases were tampered with including the bombings of
the World Trade Center, the Oklahoma City federal building and an
Avianca Airlines jet, he said.
</P>
<P>
Inspector General Michael Bromwich told a news conference that
Whitehurst "raised some valid concerns." He added, however, "We
did not substantiate the majority of his allegations, including
his most inflammatory charges of perjury and fabrication."
</P>
<P>
The report cites a slew of "serious and significant
deficiencies," including the use of scientifically flawed
testimony, inadequate documentation of test results,
scientifically flawed reports, and poor record-keeping.
It recommended a number of personnel changes within the lab.
</P>
</TEXT>
