<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Shares Up on Benign US Inflation Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
recovered from Monday's losses and rallied strongly today,
boosted by benign US inflation data today which to some extent
eased worries about higher US interest rates.
</P>
<P>
British shares closed with solid gains after tracking a strong
rally on Wall Street, inspired by a modest 0.1 percent rise in US
consumer prices in March, with the FTSE 100 index up 35.1 points,
or 0.83 percent, at 4,286.8.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the subdued inflation figures restored
investors' confidence and quashed fears of an imminent US interest
rate hike and a sharp bond sell-off.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares closed at higher levels achieved
earlier on the Dow's overnight gains, but failed to build on
initial gains as caution set in ahead of the release of the US
consumer price index, with the DAX-30 index 47.78 points, or 1.46
percent, higher at 3,327.68.
</P>
<P>
On the Paris bourse, French shares also closed sharply higher
in line with stronger international markets, with the CAC-40 index
up 54.5 points, or 2.12 percent, at 2,620.63.
</P>
<P>
The market was supported by a bullish outlook for monetary
union, a firmer dollar and Wall Street's early gains, traders
said.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index of leading British shares ended up 35.1
points at 4,286.8. The Frankfurt DAX-30 index finished 47.78
points higher at 3,327.68. In Paris, the CAC-40 index closed 54.5
points up at 2,620.63. 
</P>
</TEXT>
