<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gorbachev Says NATO Expansion A Mistake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Former Soviet Union leader
Mikhail Gorbachev today said that the expansion of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) is a "bad mistake."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the U.S. Congress here, Gorbachev said, "The whole
idea is wrong... a bad mistake."
</P>
<P>
But he added that Russia's opposition to the alliance's
expansion could be mitigated if NATO commits itself to
non-deployment of nuclear weapons, combat forces and military
infrastructure in the new members.
</P>
<P>
The 16-member alliance is scheduled to convene a special summit
in Madrid in July and will invite some of the Eastern and Central
European countries as new members. The plan was strongly opposed
by Russia.
</P>
<P>
NATO and Russia are now negotiating a document that will shape
their future relationship. The negotiations are expected to
conclude by the end of next month.
</P>
<P>
Gorbachev, who was the last leader of the former Soviet Union,
is now in Washington to attend a U.S. congressional meeting on
non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and components. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
