<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US to Provide More Food Aid to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- In response to an emergency
appeal from the World Food Program, the United States has decided
to provide an additional food aid to the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) for its children, the State Department
announced today.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told reporters at a
regular briefing that the United States has decided to provide 15
million dollar additional food aid because it was convinced by the
assessment by the World Food Program that "the food situation in
North Korea will reach a critical stage this spring."
</P>
<P>
The new food aid, on top of 10 million dollars promised in
February, was offered on the eve of crucial talks to be held
Wednesday in New York between the DPRK and the United States and
South Korea about a U.S.-South Korean proposal of four-party peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
But Burns denied there weres any links between the food aid and
the upcoming talks. The U.S. announcement of new food aid came a
day before the New York talks, Burns said.
</P>
<P>
Even if Pyongyang does not agree to enter into the talks
Wednesday, the food aid will go forward, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
