<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Ministers Reach Agreement on Fishing Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
fisheries ministers meeting in Luxembourg adopted today by a
qualified majority plans to slash fish catches to safeguard
endangered stocks and ensure the survival of European fishing
industry.
</P>
<P>
According to local radio reports, it was agreed at the two-day
meeting that endangered and overfished stocks would be cut by
respectively 30 percent and 20 percent over the next five years to
the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, member states are given the flexibility in
choosing whether to cut fish catches by laying up vessels, or
reducing fishing effort -- time spent hunting stocks in targeted
areas with specified gear -- or a combination of both.
</P>
<P>
Britain voted against the deal, insisting that the EU must
first solve the problem of "quota hoppers" -- vessels from one EU
state which register in another to take part of its quota.
</P>
<P>
Around 20 percent of the British national fish quota is now
allocated to 150 foreign vessels, mainly Spanish and Dutch,
legally registered under the British flag.
</P>
<P>
France, which wanted a 15 percent cut, also voted against.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
