<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Envoy to Salvage Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. envoy Dennis Ross is
heading for the Middle East to present new U.S. proposals to
Israel and the Palestinians in an attempt to salvage the moribund
peace process, the State Department said today.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told reporters that
Ross will meet separately with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, seeking their
responses to the U.S. new proposals for resumption of peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"He's going to be pursuing with both of them a continuation of
the discussions that President Clinton and Secretary (Madeleine)
Albright had with the Israelis, that Secretary Albright had with
the Palestinian delegation last week," Burns said.
</P>
<P>
The United States hopes the new proposals "might bridge the
differences between them," he added. "We need responses from them
obviously at some point. We want to talk through in more detail
what we have in mind. And we want to resurrect the peace
negotiations."
</P>
<P>
The latest U.S. proposals come a month after violence flared up
between Israelis and Palestinians over Israel's violation of peace
agreements by deciding to build 6,500 Jewish homes in
traditionally Arab east Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zairean People Hope to Return to Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KISANGANI, April 15 (Xinhua) -- It is the urgent task for
eastern Zaire and the whole country to return to peace and
stability to ease poverty and improve Zaireans's life, said Yagi
Sitolo, Governor of Eastern Province, here today.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, he lamented that
"everything has been destroyed. We have no basis. We must do
everything ourselves for rehabilitation step by step."
</P>
<P>
Sitolo, a doctor running a clinic in Kisangani, was elected as
Governor of the diamond-rich province (formally known as Upper
Zaire) by local chiefs and well-known residents after rebel
troops led by Laurent Kabila seized the city on March 15.
</P>
<P>
He urged his people to change the habit of waiting for grants
and assistance and work hard to promote production.
</P>
<P>
The most urgent need is to improve conditions of security,
communication and health care, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Security is being improved. Banditry, robbery and other
violent crimes, rampant in the past, are reducing after the city
fell to the rebel troops, said Sitolo.
</P>
<P>
However, communication and health environment are in mess,
said local residents. All the roads in Kisangani have been
damaged and during the current rainy season, it is very difficult
to drive in the streets.
</P>
<P>
Roads leading to the outside are even worse. It took the
Xinhua reporter two hours to arrive by car at a refugee camp
which is only 26 kilometers away from the city.
</P>
<P>
Along the street rubbishes are seen now and there, although
cholera, malaria and other epidemics are posing threats to the
local people.
</P>
<P>
Once peace and stability return to the central African
country, foreigners will be welcome to come to join the Zaireans
to explore diamonds in the region, he added.
</P>
<P>
"If we want foreigners to live in our country, we must rule it
with good governance and build it with hard work first," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
