<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FT Launches Video-on-Demand Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The British newspaper, the
Financial Times, launched at its headquarters today a
video-on-demand service that is set to dramatically change the way
in which companies communicate with institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
The service, called Veritas, will deliver live and on-demand
video coverage of corporate announcements, analysts' meetings and
presentations directly to the desktops of individual fund
managers.
</P>
<P>
In addition it will provide industry sector video reports and
market information presented through special news bulletins each
working day.
</P>
<P>
It will also have regular commentary from financial analysts
(including morning briefing summaries from Natwest Markets the
leading City analysts) and interviews with chief executive
officers.
</P>
<P>
The service will be brought together by the Financial Times and
distributed via satellite to a closely targeted financial audience
across Europe and the key financial centers of America.
</P>
<P>
Launching the service, Ad Barerjee, managing director of
Veritas, said: "There is a real need for institutional
shareholders and quoted company management to communicate with
each other in an efficient and easy-to-use way."
</P>
<P>
"After extensive research into the nature of corporate
information supplied to the financial markets....Veritas is
designed specifically to meet that need," he added.
</P>
<P>
Trials of Veritas have proved the popularity of the service;
the combined market capitalization of the companies that have
joined the service to date is over 200 billion pounds (320 billion
US dollars).
</P>
<P>
It was announced that the institutional investors currently
installing Veritas represent 65 percent to 70 percent of the UK
funds under management, which includes eight out of the ten
largest institutions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
