<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford 1st Quarter Earnings Jump to 1.5 Billion US Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Ford Motor Co., the second
largest automaker in the U.S., said today its first-quarter profit
more than doubled from a year ago to 1.5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The results exceeded Wall Street's expectations.
</P>
<P>
Ford's automotive operations earned 1 billion U.S. dollars, a
seven-fold increase from the 142 million U.S. dollars they netted
a year ago. Its first-quarter U.S. automotive profits were 836
million U.S. dollars, compared with 48 million U.S. dollars a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
Ford attributed its improved performance to sales of
higher-profit vehicles and its Ford 2000 cost-cutting program.
</P>
<P>
Earnings from Ford's international automotive operations were
less impressive but still showed improvement at 168 million U.S.
dollars, up from 94 million U.S. dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The company earned from its European auto operations 105
million U.S. dollars, compared with 73 million U.S. dollars in the
first quarter of 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
