<HEADLINE> France Reaffirms Support to Mobutu-Kabila Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 16 (Xinhua) -- France today reaffirmed its support
to a possible meeting between Zairian President Mobutu Sese Seko
and the country's rebel leader Laurent-Desire Kabila to find a
solution to the conflict of the country.
</P>
<P>
The French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said
that France would be "delighted" if such a meeting could take
place "very rapidly."
</P>
<P>
He said that such a meeting should be "an opportunity"for
peace, if the warring sides of Zaire wish to "achieve in the
shortest time decisive advances toward a peaceful solution."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the objective of such a meeting should
be the "definite stop of hostilities, implementation of the
(United Nations) peace plan, and the organization of an orderly
political transition period, in perspective of free elections
observed by the international community."
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader Kabila is now in South Africa where he will
meet with President Nelson Mandela this evening. 
</P>
