<HEADLINE>   KEDO' Visit to Pyongyang Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 16 (Xinhua) -- A delegation from the Korean
Peninsula Energy Development Organization (KEDO) said today
progress has been made on the construction of nuclear reactors and
other issues in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
KEDO, the U.S.-led international consortium set up to provide
two 1,000 megawatt nuclear reactors to the DPRK, sent a 54-member
team to the country for an eight-day visit on April 8 to negotiate
pre-construction issues.
</P>
<P>
The head of the delegation, Choi Young-jin, KEDO's deputy
executive director, told the press today the team conducted
on-site investigations in east-coast Shinpo city, where the
reactors will be constructed.
</P>
<P>
The delegation and the DPRK reached agreement on entry and
exit procedures for construction workers from South Korea and
other countries, Choi said.
</P>
<P>
Progress was also made in communications, the postal service,
and the use of local manpower in the project. But Choi said more
time was needed to reach agreement on all construction-related
issues with Pyongyang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
