<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Chee Hwa on Hong Kong's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The year of 1997 is a momentous
 year for all the people in Hong Kong and the citizens have a
unique opportunity to shape Hong Kong's future, according to Tung
Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
Addressing a gathering of the Canadian Chamber of Commerce this
evening, Tung said that under the concept of "one country, two
systems," Hong Kong's high degree of autonomy is guaranteed by the
Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
He said the future well-being of Hong Kong is very much tied to
China, stressing that the long-term interests of Hong Kong and
China are the same.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We must constantly remind ourselves that we are part
of China. We are of one country. We need to constantly remind
ourselves that whatever we do in Hong Kong, we must take into
consideration China's objective of continuing to create wealth for
all Chinese people."
</P>
<P>
On Hong Kong's future development, Tung expressed the
confidence that Hong Kong will achieve its goals in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
"We have a strong fiscal reserve; we have a high-quality civil
service; we are committed to the rule of law and free enterprises
and free trade," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We have the commitment of the people of Hong Kong to
make our community a better place in the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
On the development of Hong Kong's education, Tung said that in
order to achieve all of Hong Kong's long-term goals, a
community-wide commitment to education will be vital.
</P>
<P>
Education is critical not only for sustaining economic
vitality, but also for giving everyone in the community an equal
opportunity to succeed, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said, "It is my firm conviction that the most important
objectives of education are to train the mind and strengthen the
spirit.
</P>
<P>
"Our education system needs to focus more on skills training,
but we also need to place more emphasis on strengthening the
character and morals of the next generation."
</P>
<P>
He said that on July 1, Hong Kong will become a special
administrative region of China. This day will symbolize the
beginning of a new era for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"At this significant juncture in our history," he said, "it
will be appropriate for us to re-identify ourselves. We need to
instill in our young people a clear identity that they are
Chinese."
</P>
<P>
"We need to renew our commitment to the traditional Chinese
virtues of modesty, hard-work, persistence, magnanimity to foes,
loyalty to friends, respect for seniors, emphasis on obligations
rather than individual rights and the willingness to sacrifice
one's interests for the common good," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
He said it is important that the entire Hong Kong community
together renews its commitment to education and to show greater
respect and appreciation for educators.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that for the 1997-98 fiscal year, Hong Kong's
total expenditure for education will be 45 billion HK dollars (6
billion U.S. dollars), which is about 21 percent of the total
public expenditure and the largest item of expenditure in the
budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
