<HEADLINE> Hungary to Reward Olympic Champions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Hungary set up a law on
Wednesday to reward its Olympic champions with a lifelong monthly
payment, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The law stipulates that resident Hungarians over the age of 36
who have gold medals from summer or winter Olympics, won either
individually or in teams, will be entitled to an annuity from
January 1 next year equivalent to the national average salary,
reports added.
</P>
<P>
The widow or widower of an Olympic champion will be eligible
for half the award, provided the couple lived together up the
champion's death.
</P>
<P>
The payout this year will cost the Hungarian state an estimated
50 million forints (about 277,000 U.S. dollars). Hungary has 139
Olympic champions and 16 of them are under 36. 
</P>
</TEXT>
