<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanxi Farmers Elect New Village Leadership (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to preliminary statistics, More than 80 percent of
the villages held multi-candidates elections this year, some
villages even saw several dozens of candidates running for six or
seven positions in the villagers' committee.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that about 30 percent of the members in
previous villagers' committees have lost the election.
</P>
<P>
More than 85 percent of the villagers all around the province
participated in the election, while the previous election in 1993
received ballots from no more than 80 percent of villagers.
</P>
<P>
Some villagers asked the departments of civil affairs for
written texts of the Organization Law of the Villagers'
Committee. Others turned to governments at higher levels to
complain illegal actions in the election, some of them even made
appeals by sending telegrams to the Provincial Department of Civil
affairs.
</P>
<P>
"This shows that farmers in this province have improved their
awareness of democracy, learned to use laws and other methods to
safeguard their democratic rights," said Guo, who attributed the
progress to more than a decade of painstaking efforts and the
accumulation of experience from the three previous elections.
</P>
<P>
He said that the province has made three breakthroughs in the
election procedures, which provided villagers more opportunities
to express their wishes freely and extensively.
</P>
<P>
The new changes include an extensive primary election, in which
everyone can vote in deciding the formal candidates, election
speeches, and specially-designated balloting rooms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanxi Farmers Elect New Village Leadership (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- "It is the first time that our
village has held an election with such a high turn-out," said Hao
Gensheng with a contented smile.
</P>
<P>
Hao, 58, is a resident of Baiyangshu Village on the outskirts
of Taiyuan City, capital of north China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
On March 18, he and nearly 400 fellow villagers above 18
elected their new villagers' committee, or village leadership,
through secret balloting.
</P>
<P>
"The election was multi-candidate, which resulted in intense
competition," said Hao, adding that the old director of the
villagers' committee failed early in the nomination process since
his work couldn't satisfy most villagers.
</P>
<P>
A self-employed man, who is not a member of the Chinese
Communist Party and has no experience in serving as a village head,
was elected new village chief.
</P>
<P>
With a term of three years, the villagers' committee is defined
as a grassroots organization of farmers' self-management in the
Chinese countryside.
</P>
<P>
According to the Law on the Organization of the Villagers'
Committee, which was adopted by the National People's Congress in
1987, members of the committee must be chosen by the villagers
through direct election.
</P>
<P>
Four elections of villagers' committees have been held in
Shanxi since 1987. The current one, which started last spring, by
this month has been completed in over 27,000 villages, over 85
percent of the province's total.
</P>
<P>
The Shanxi Provincial Department of Civil Affairs, which is
overseeing the village election, recently announced that the
current election was almost over, and the rest of the work would
be finished within this year.
</P>
<P>
To date, a new round of village election has ended in most
parts of the country. Elections are still going on in three other
provinces -- Hebei, Fujian, and Heilongjiang.
</P>
<P>
Guo Xiaoping, deputy director of the Shanxi Provincial
Department of Civil Affairs, described the direct election of
villagers' committee as a cornerstone of China's system of
villagers' self-management.
</P>
<P>
"Letting farmers freely choose whom they trust as village
leaders, will not only consolidate rural political power, but also
help solve problems haunting rural management, such as taxation,
public security, and family planning," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the current village election in Shanxi is highly
democratic, and represents "historic progress" in the building of
democratic politics at the grassroots level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanxi Villagers Elect New Leadership (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Information from the departments of civil affairs showed that
problems still cropped up in the election of villagers'
committees. For example, some township officials interfered in the
election, smoothing the way for their trusted village cadres to be
reelected, under the pretext of maintaining stability.
</P>
<P>
Elections in some places were seriously affected by the
influence of patriarchal clans and factions. A handful of people
attempted to manipulate the voting by illegal means.
</P>
<P>
Guo said that the strict supervision by the departments of
civil affairs over the election procedures and the severe
punishment of the illegal acts may help to reduce the problems.
</P>
<P>
But the arduous process of democratic practices will still be
needed to cultivate and raise the awareness of democracy of
village cadres and villagers before those problems are solved, he
added.
</P>
<P>
"Not all the newly-elected village cadres are qualified, due to
influence of patriarchal clans and other adverse effects." said
Guo, "But we usually support the election as long as it is legal
and valid, and represents the wishes of villagers. Villagers
can still dismiss the cadres if they fail to do their jobs well."
</P>
<P>
Democratic election is just the first step to the
self-management of villagers, Guo said, but to make sure that the
villagers' committees can really represent the interests of the
villagers, village councils, and the publicizing of the work of
village cadres should be introduced to rural areas and the
mechanism of democratic decision-making, management, and
supervision, be established and improved.
</P>
<P>
"The democratic decision-making, management, and supervision,
along with the village election, will all play a vital role in
promoting democratic politics in rural areas," he concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
