<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Egyptian Bitterness Shrouds Association </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 16 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian-EU partnership deal
augurs well for signing after nine rounds of laborious talks
until Egypt cried foul, demanding a balanced treatment to its
agricultural exports and the disadvantaged south, in general.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa has blasted the European
Union proposals for clinching the economic association deal with
Egypt as "imbalanced" and threatened to quit if Europe imposes its
interests at others' expense.
</P>
<P>
The whole row started as Egypt and the EU expected to sign the
association agreement at the two-day EU-Mediterranean conference,
which opened in Velletta, Malta, Tuesday to promote the
partnership forged between 15 EU countries and 12 south
Mediterranean partners in Barcelona in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The two sides had held nine rounds of talks since January 1995
in a bid to reach the deal, which would provide for establishing a
free trade zone between them in the 12 years following the
formation of partnership ties.
</P>
<P>
But then Egypt charged that the EU proposals would put it in a
disadvantage by giving European manufactures free access to the
Egyptian market but keeping quotas on exports of Egyptian food,
the area where Cairo has the best prospects.
</P>
<P>
Egypt fears that its own products are blocked from reaching the
European markets while it is among the largest importers of
European meat and agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
"It would not be worthwhile to sign an agreement which fails to
provide fair market access for both manufactured goods and
agricultural products," said Moussa.
</P>
<P>
He said the only obvious benefit to Egypt would be EU aid
to help Egyptian industry adapt to the competition.
</P>
<P>
At the opening session of the gathering of EU and Mediterranean
foreign ministers, the furious Moussa went further to suspect the
Euro-Mediterranean dialogue a mere "tactical move" that makes "the
countries of the south pay the price in the long term in return
for the assistance they need in the short term."
</P>
<P>
In fact, the partnership talks have bumped all the way until
the EU countries agreed to increase the quotas on the most
controversial commodities, such as rice, potatoes, citrus fruit
and cut flowers, at the latest round of talks on March 10-12.
</P>
<P>
But Moussa insisted they were still inadequate and more
concessions are needed.
</P>
<P>
He demanded an agreement that would ensure a fair and balanced
access for agricultural and industrial commodities and provide
proper financial support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
