<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Egyptian Bitterness Shrouds Association </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Now Egypt is frustrated and
suspicious about whether EU has a "genuine and equitable political
will" to conclude an agreement with Egypt that conforms with the
true spirit of partnership, Moussa told the conference in
Velletta, Malta.
</P>
<P>
Egypt argued that its agricultural quota should be scaled up,
under the world trade accord, to a level higher than when it
traded with the Soviet Union and eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Even from the beginning, the partnership negotiations have been
difficult and crucial as the European countries represents 46
percent of Egypt's foreign trade, according to Egyptian Minister
of Trade and Supply Ahmed Goweili.
</P>
<P>
During a week-long European tour in March, Goweili got
assurances of easier Egyptian access to the European markets for
customs-free items such as rice, potatoes, flowers and citrus
fruits.
</P>
<P>
But the agricultural file remains the most thorny part of the
14-item partnership agreement covering all fields of cooperation,
when each of the 15 EU nations harbors fears about the negative
impact of the Egyptian agricultural exports on its own production.
</P>
<P>
For example, Spain has a problem with orange, the Netherlands
with flowers and Germany with potatoes. The result was that the
Egyptian suggestions to raise the traditional level of these
tariff-exempt exports had been cold-shouldered.
</P>
<P>
Egypt suffers a trade deficit of about 2.7 million ECUs with
the EU in 1995 when foodstuffs account for 9 percent of its total
exports.
</P>
<P>
EU has already forged partnership with Morocco, Tunis and
Israel, and is yet to sign agreements with Egypt, Jordan and
Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Leader Warns Germany of Paying Heavy Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Supreme Leader Ali
Khamenei today warned Germany of paying a heavy price for the
Mykonos verdict a week ago, Tehran Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei made the strong-worded statement on the occasion of
the Armed Forces Day, which was attended by top Iranian military
brass and some high-ranking government officials.
</P>
<P>
This is the first statement he has made since the verdict of
the Berlin court which charged top Iranian leaders with ordering
the killing of four Kurdish opposition leaders in Mykonos
restaurant in Berlin in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei said that "Germany has paid a heavy price and will
continue to pay, and it would have to face all the consequences of
its deeds."
</P>
<P>
But observers here noted that the warning by the Iranian
supreme leader is just a warning. Iran can not afford to lose
Europe after it severed relations with the United States
18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
They said that it seems impossible for Iran to take the
initiative to reduce or sever the diplomatic relations with
Germany or other European countries.
</P>
<P>
Tehran even would not limit its trade and economic relations
with European countries. It is totally against Iran's national
interest to take such an action. Iran's vital projects are relied
on European technology, with Germany in particular, they added.
</P>
<P>
Germany is Iran's largest trade partner, which takes a lion's
share in Iran's total import and export. German exports to Iran
made up 41.3 percent of the total import of Iran while German
imports from Iran accounted for 32.8 percent of the total export
of Iran in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei said that the Mykonos case or the Berlin court's
ruling was in fact a joint U.S.-Israeli conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that Iran would never retract even one step
vis-a-vis the bullying by the Clinton administration or any other
government.
</P>
<P>
"Iran only relies on its own faith and nothing else," he
added.
</P>
<P>
In response to the Berlin court verdict, Iran has launched a
nationwide anti-German wave with various kinds of demonstrations
in 12 cities over the past few days.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) nations have now withdrawn their
ambassadors from Iran, who are expected to meet in Brussels
Thursday. EU's ministerial level meeting will make a unified
action toward Iran in Brussels on April 29. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
