<HEADLINE> Russian Deputy FM Meets Lebanese Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Victor Posevalyuk, Russia's
deputy foreign minister for the Middle East affairs, expressed
here today his country's "worry and pessimism" over an
aggravation of the situation in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Posevalyuk, who arrived here from the Syrian capital of
Damascus earlier this morning on the second leg of his tour in
the region, held a meeting with Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri in the latter's office.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters following the end of the meeting, the
Russian official said that they discussed the situation in the
region, and exchanged views on how to revive the peace process
from the current stalemate.
</P>
<P>
Posevalyuk described as "useful" the ideas put forward by the
Lebanese premier. He said that his mission focused on meetings
with the officials of the countries concerned in the peace
process, in addition to making contacts with Dennis Ross, the
U.S. Middle East peace coordinator, and Miguel Angel Moratinos,
the European Union's Middle East peace envoy.
</P>
<P>
The deputy foreign minister added that he will report to
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov the results of his tour
in order to work out measures to be taken for Russia's diplomacy
in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
On the results of Hariri's visit to Moscow last week, the
Russian official said that the two sides had signed in Moscow a
number of economic accords which "should become a proper framework
of works for developing the relations between Russia and Lebanon."
</P>
<P>
"We are not satisfied with the current level of these
relations," he noted, saying that the two sides had reached an
understanding that more steps are needed in the future.
</P>
<P>
After the talks with the Lebanese premier, Posevalyuk left
Beirut for Jordan's capital Amman.
</P>
<P>
The Russian official will also visit Israel and the
Palestinian self-rule area of Gaza. 
</P>
