<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Level Down in Caspian Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The recent drop of the Caspian
Sea's water level has prompted scientists to believe that the
amount of water at the salt-water lake fluctuate periodically.
</P>
<P>
The Caspian Sea, the world's largest in-land lake of the kind,
was found to be down an average of 20 centimeters in water level
last year, reversing the continuous rise in previous years.
</P>
<P>
The discovery, said a report in the fortnightly Ecological
Messenger magazine published here today, was made by scientists
working with Azerbaijan's State Hydrology Committee.
</P>
<P>
Based on the new finding, S. Velelv, an Azerbaijani
geophysicist, assumed that the phenomenon could be the start of a
trend of lower water level through the middle of next century.
</P>
<P>
However, a probable long period of less water in the lake would
be in sharp contrast to what had happened until last year.
</P>
<P>
Since 1978, the surface of the Caspian Sea had risen 2.4 meters
on average, drowning seven residential areas, 200 oil wells and
650,000 hectares of farm land in Kazakhstan alone.
</P>
<P>
The swell of the lake was theorized last year by S. Shelo, an
academician with the Russian Academy of Sciences, as a result of
the periodical movement of earth crusts.
</P>
<P>
Under the pressure coming along with the movement, he said,
underground water are squeezed upward and poured into the Caspian
Sea, leading to the rise of water level.
</P>
<P>
But once the huge amount of water builds up enough tension, the
Russian scientist said, surface water could be "swallowed" back
down and result in a lower water level.
</P>
<P>
He predicted, somehow in line with what his Azerbaijani
counterpart assumed recently, that the water level of the Caspian
Sea would be down starting from sometime between 2005 and 2020.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
