<HEADLINE> Chemical Warfare Victims Protest against Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- More than 10,000 victims of Iraqi
chemical warfare during the 1980-88 war between Iran and Iraq
staged a protest rally in front of the German Embassy this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Some of the victims are moving on wheelchairs on the streets
and some are families of the killed, urging Iranian justice
department to prosecute German firms supplying Iraq with toxic
gas and technology to launch chemical attacks against Iranian
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Holding the effigies of a Berlin court judge, the war veterans
bearing white breathing masks carried the photos of their fellow
combatants who had succumbed to their chemical wounds as well as
models of missiles containing toxic gas used by Iraqi soldiers in
the eight-year bitter war.
</P>
<P>
The veterans urged Iran's justice department to proceed with
their complaints and take legal actions at the international
level against the German firms supplying chemical and biological
weapons to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
They called on the German government to apologize to Iran for
what they called the blunder made by the Berlin court in the
trial charging top Iranian leaders of ordering the killing of
four Kurdish opposition leaders in the Mykonos Restaurant
of Berlin in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Just three days before the verdict was announced, Iranian
judicial authorities demanded 24 German firms and a number of
German government officials to appear in an Iranian court on
charges of supplying the chemical weapon to Iraq during the
Iran-Iraq war in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the judicial branch said that the families of
the victims and the disabled by the chemical weapons asked for
compensation to their sufferings and losses of their lives and
punishment of German chemical weapon exporters and a number of
government officials who issued the permit for the export of the
chemical weapons to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The anonymous spokesman claimed that there are valid and
undeniable documents such as pictures, films and speeches from
German technicians who were working and cooperating with the Iraqi
army on the deployment of the chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
Last December, Iran accused 84 German companies, including
Toysen, Zigma and Hebergerbau, of supplying chemical weapons to
Iraq during the war.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah Mazandarani, Secretary General of the Association for
Helping Victims of Iraq's Chemical Warfare, said that Iran has
collected a considerable volume of information regarding Germany
in connection with the chemical weapon supplies to Iraq during
the eight-year war.
</P>
<P>
He said that some 25,000 Iranians were killed and 65,000
Iranian veterans were injured in the war as victims of chemical
bombs.
</P>
<P>
"In addition to German firms there were some 18 American and
British firms that were supplying the Iraqis," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that most of the bombs were given to Baghdad under
the cover of providing pesticide to Iraqis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0105 </DOCNO>
