<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Delays Launching Bond in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Central Bank has
decided to delay the launch of the country's 1.25 billion U.S.
dollars of Yankee bond in the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
Central bank governor Gabriel Singson announced the decision in
a press release issued today by the Presidential Press Office.
</P>
<P>
The launch of the bond was reset in the light of the highly
unfavorable market conditions that have prevailed in the last few
days in the U.S. bond market, Singson said.
</P>
<P>
Salomon Brothers, a famous U.S. investment firm which was in
charge of issuing the bond, agreed with the decision, said
Singson, who is now in the U.S. to prepare for the launch of the
bond.
</P>
<P>
The bond was initially scheduled to be launched in the U.S. on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Singson said the current market conditions have resulted in the
sudden and sharp increase in the interest rate on the U.S.
Treasury 30-year bond as well as the widening of spreads asked for
by investors.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, economists had warned the central bank against
launching the bond at this time because the bank will have to pay
higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The central bank will quickly come back to the U.S. market to
launch the bond at a much more favorable and appropriate price
than what can be obtained under present difficult overall market
conditions, Singson said.
</P>
<P>
In view of its sustained high economic growth, the Philippines
wants to launch the 1.25 billion dollars Yankee bond to boost its
international reserves.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
