<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Securities Market Important to China's Economy: Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The securities market has become
an important part of China's socialist market economic system,
senior government securities officials said at an international
conference here today.
</P>
<P>
"The securities market has played a positive role in pooling
funds, transforming the operating mechanism of Chinese
enterprises, and optimizing the distribution of resources," Zhou
Zhengqing, chairman of the Securities Committee of the State
Council, said at the opening session of a conference of the
Asia-Pacific Regional Committee of the International Organization
Securities Committee (IOSCO), which also functions as a symposium
on Asian-Pacific securities markets.
</P>
<P>
China will further tap the role of the securities market in
raising capital and transforming the operating mechanism of
enterprises, and will give keen support to the state-owned
enterprises to issue shares or convertible bonds, said Zhou, who
is also Deputy Secretary-General of the State Council, or the
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Daojiong, chairman of China Securities Regulatory
Commission (CSRC), said that China has always attached importance
to standardizing the securities market and has over the years
promulgated a number of securities laws, rules and regulations.
</P>
<P>
"As our market expands, we should establish an effective system
and mechanism to guard against market risks," he said.
</P>
<P>
CSRC, China's securities industry watchdog, joined IOSCO, a
standing international organization established in 1983 and
headquartered in Montreal, Canada, in 1995.
</P>
<P>
China's securities market has basically taken shape after rapid
development in the six years since its establishment. By the end
of February, there were 561 companies listed on the country's two
stock exchanges in Shanghai and Shenzhen, with a market
capitalization of more than 1.16 trillion yuan.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 87 Chinese companies have issued inside the
country shares exclusively for overseas investors, raising a total
of 3.9 billion US dollars in capital. Another 29 Chinese firms
have listed on overseas bourses and pooled 5.9 billion US dollars
in the aggregate.
</P>
<P>
Today's conference, which will last through Friday, drew
securities officials and experts from India, Australia, Malaysia,
Japan, Thailand, Singapore, and Hong Kong, as well as officials
and experts from a number of Chinese government departments, such
as the State Planning Commission and the People's Bank of China,
the central bank.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
