<HEADLINE> Chinese Securities Legislation at Critical Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- China's securities legislation
has entered a crucial period in its long-term process of
establishment and perfection, a senior legislative official
said today.
</P>
<P>
"In view of the emerging but immature Chinese securities market,
the task to establish a complete legal framework becomes all the
more urgent, and to establish a unified securities market in
China, uniformity of legislation should be pursued," said Bian
Yaowu, deputy director of the Commission of Legislative Affairs
of the Standing Committee of National People's Congress, China's
top legislature, at an international conference of securities
regulatory committees.
</P>
<P>
The official pointed out that securities trading rules will be
an important part of the upcoming securities law, in order to
ensure orderly and safe securities transactions.
</P>
<P>
"The law should provide severe penalties on illegal activities
like insider trading and securities price manipulation," Bian
said, adding that the legal framework will also take into account
regulations on information disclosure and access to the securities
industry.
</P>
<P>
The legal official also called for stock exchanges to be
further standardized, saying that stock exchanges should be set up
only in a small number and adopt unified forms and standards, and
the law also needs to cover qualifications, rights, and duties of
their staff.
</P>
<P>
China has formulated a series of securities regulations and
rules since 1993, and the draft Securities Law is still being
examined by the nation's legislative body, said Bian.
</P>
<P>
He also hailed the inclusion of securities crimes in the new
criminal law as a "necessary act" to standardize the market for a
sustained and sound development.
</P>
<P>
"A primary goal of securities legislation is to protect the
investors, and to do this, we also need to turn to the power of
the law to further standardize the market and curb
excessive speculation and irregularities," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPC Reaffirms its Commitment to Clean and Honest Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Communist Party of China
(CPC) reaffirms its commitment to build a clean and honest
government by banning its senior officials from engaging in
personal profit-seeking and other activities.
</P>
<P>
In a code of conduct for the senior CPC officials, which was
issued recently, the CPC Central Committee places a ban on its
senior officials from engaging in the following activities:
</P>
<P>
- seeking improper gains by taking advantage of one's position
and power;
</P>
<P>
- using public office for personal gain;
</P>
<P>
- seeking personal gain by taking the opportunity of promoting
someone else;
</P>
<P>
- seeking gains for relatives, family members, and close
friends by using the influence of one's position and power;
</P>
<P>
- Squandering public funds, extravagance, and waste.
</P>
<P>
The document also bans spouses and children of officials above
provincial and ministerial level from running private businesses
or being employed in solely overseas-funded enterprises in the
region under the officials' jurisdiction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
