<HEADLINE> ANA Donates to Building a School in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- All Nippon Airways (ANA), one of
the leading carriers in Japan, has donated 300,000 yuan to China's
Hope Project for building a primary school in Hebei province.
</P>
<P>
ANA made the donation upon the tenth anniversary of the first
air routes to China. The money will be used to build a primary
school named ANA Blue Sky Hope Primary School in Sandigoumen
Village about 150 km from Beijing, according to Seiji Fukatsu,
ANA's president and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
The school, built for about 200 school-age children in the
village, is scheduled to open on September 1.
</P>
<P>
ANA operates nine services between Tokyo and Osaka and Beijng,
Dalian, Shanghai, Qingdao, and Hong Kong which is scheduled to
return to the motherland on July 1, said Fukatsu. The carrier
initiated its first China-Japan route in April, 1987.
</P>
<P>
He added the passenger flow on ANA's China-Japan routes surged
six times over the past decade, and it now accounts for one forth
of the total on the carrier's international routes.
</P>
<P>
"We have already regarded the routes to China as the most
important market for our international service," Fukatsu noted,
adding that ANA is applying for permission to extend services to
Tianjin, Shenyang, and other Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
The International Air Transport Association estimates that air
transport in the Asia-Pacific region will make up half of the
world's total, and that between China and Japan will expand
especially rapidly.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
