<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Average Growth Estimated at 2.9 Pct: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Australia's annual economic
growth would be at an average of 2.9 percent in the remaining
years of this decade, but it would be still faster than the
average growth of 2.7 percent projected for the world economy
during 1996-2000.
</P>
<P>
The estimates were given today by the Economic and Social
Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP).
</P>
<P>
In comparison, the average economic growth rate predicted by
the Australian Government in its last year's budget was 3.5
percent, and in order to reduce unemployment, the country needs to
keep its growth rate at 4.5 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
ESCAP expects Australia's inflation rate to climb to an average
of 3.4 percent. Last month Treasurer Peter Costello said inflation
remained the key determining factor in setting official interest
rates in Australia.
</P>
<P>
An ESCAP survey for 1997 projected annual gross domestic
product (GDP) growth for economies in the region, at 6.7 percent a
year, slower than that in the past five years, and Australia's GDP
growth is expected to be below the average.  
</P>
</TEXT>
