<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Receive Two Million Overseas Visitors in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Over two million overseas people
are estimated to tour Shanghai in the year of 2000, bringing the
city 17 billion yuan (more than two billion U.S. dollars) of
tourism income.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Shanghai vice-mayor Chen Liangyu at a
convention of the Pacific Asian Travel Association (PATA) here
today.
</P>
<P>
Chen told the convention that Shanghai has made a profit of
1.17 billion U.S. dollars by receiving over 1.4 million tourists
last year, an increase of 3.7 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is expected to receive nearly 200,000 visitors more
each year, said Chen.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has become a tourist destination for seven overseas
visitors out of every ten.
</P>
<P>
Chen, one of the city's decision-makers, said that Shanghai is
making tourism a new economic growth area of the city.
</P>
<P>
Experts believed that it is possible for Shanghai tourism to
grow at an annual speed of eight percent. Shanghai used to be the
most important metropolis of industry, economy, trade, and culture
in China's modern history.
</P>
<P>
Currently Shanghai is a leading city across the country in
terms of development pace, scale, and economic returns of tourism.
</P>
<P>
The Municipal government has announced Tuesday that two
agencies were formed to outline comprehensive plans of tourism and
coordinate the city's tourism development.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has over 260 travel agents, 118 star-level hotels with
over 30,000 rooms, and over 50 high schools and colleges of
tourism.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai connects itself with nearly 90 domestic and overseas
cities in the air as it has become the hub of over 300 air
routes. This largest port city of China also receives some 20
luxury pleasure boats each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
