<HEADLINE> Zairean Rebel Leader Kabila Leaves Zaire for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Zairean rebel leader Laurent
Kabila left Lubumbashi, southern Zaire, today for South Africa to
discuss the Zairean crisis with President Nelson Mandela, a
report reaching here this afternoon said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Kabila departed at 11:40 am (0940
gmt) on a South African air force jet bound for Cape Town after a
two-day visit to the second largest city of Zaire. His forces
captured the capital city of the mineral-rich Shaba Province on
April 9.
</P>
<P>
The report said, their discussions will center on arrangements
for face to face talks between Kabila and Zairean President
Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo on Tuesday
predicted "dramatic progress within days" in ending the civil war
in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The Alliance of Domocratic Forces for the Liberiation of
Congo-Zaire led by Kabila took arms last October in eastern Zaire
to topple President Mobutu. In less than six months, the rebels have
occupied more than half of the third largest country in Africa.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Kabila's forces are now 300 km away
from the Zairean capital Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
UN Secretary General Kofi Annan yesterday appealed to UN
members to press Kabila to seek a negotiated solution through a
ceasefrire and sustained talks on Zaire's future.
</P>
<P>
However, Kabila refused the appeal, saying "how can I
declare a ceasefire when the people are against one? The people
do not want a ceasefire, they want an end to this corrupt regime."
</P>
<P>
"A ceasefire would be against the people's will," he added.
enditem


