<HEADLINE> Krajicek Goes Through at Japan Open Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Richard Krajicek, moved
into top 16 at the Japan Open tennis tournament after scoring a
second-round victory Wednesday over South African Neville Godwin
6-3, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Krajicek, the 1996 Wimbledon champion, ended impressively with
a 216 kph ace and a 201 kph service winner.
</P>
<P>
The world no.6 was eliminated in the second round of the Indian
Open by Romanina's Andrei Pavel last week.
</P>
<P>
Godwin, first-round winner over Pavel here, could not afford
the fierce shots by his Dutch opponent, who served 14 aces and
broke Godwin once in each set.
</P>
<P>
In the round of 16, Krajicek faces No. 15 seed Magnus Norman of
Sweden, a 6-4, 6-2 winner over American Justin Gimelstob.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Henrik Holm, back in action this year after 10-month
layoff due to shoulder surgery, beat the Gold Flake winner, fellow
Swede Mikael Tillstrom, 4-6, 6-3, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
No. 3 seed Marc Rosset of Switzerland struggled past British
qualifier Andrew Richardson 7-6 (8-6), 2-6, 6-2. He now meets
Australian Mark Woodforde, the 13th seed, who beat Germany's
Martin Sinner 6-1, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
No. 5 Thomas Johansson of Sweden beat Canada's Daniel Nestor
6-4, 6-4, setting up a clash with Shuzo Matsuoka of Japan.
</P>
<P>
No. 6 Pat Rafter of Australia, the Salem Open runner-up to
Michael Chang in Hong Kong Monday, ousted Eyal Ran of Israel 6-0,
6-4 and next faces Holm.
</P>
<P>
In women's action, Americans Kimberly Po, top seed following
the withdrawal of Mary Joe Fernandez with a back injury, beat
another American Jolene Watanabe with an identical 6-2 to enter
the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
Po next meets fifth-seeded Wang Shi-ting of Chinese Taipei,
winner over Austrian Karen Kschwendt 6-2, 6-4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
