<HEADLINE> China's Economy Expected to Grow 8.7 Percent Annually To 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese economy will grow at
an annual rate of 8.7 percent for the remaining part of the
century, according to a report from the United Nations Economic
and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP), issued
today.
</P>
<P>
Viet Nam is expected to lead Asia and the Pacific region's
economic development with a rate of 9.9 percent, and the
Asia-Pacific region will continue to be most economically vigorous
area in the world, with its economy continuing a yearly rate of
6.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Globally, the report said, the third world's economic growth
will be ahead of that of advanced economies by 2.8 percentage
points. The former is expected to grow at 4.9 percent every year.
</P>
<P>
The report cautioned countries in the Asia-Pacific region
about demographic changes, as the ratio of elderly rises
substantially. "By the year 2020, it is estimated that the
developing economies of today will have a fourth of their
populations below the age of 25 and about 12 percent over age 60,"
the report says.
</P>
<P>
In addition, more people will move from rural to urban areas by
2020, pushing up the urban population ratio overall to 50.8
percent from the current 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
ESCAP was founded in 1947 in Shanghai and later moved its
headquarters to Bangkok. This is its 50th annual report on the
region' social and economic development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
