<HEADLINE> Subtropic Animal Fossils Found in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Subtropical animal fossils
dating back 30,000 to 100,000 years have been found in a cave in
north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
The fossils, belonging to such animals as deers, wild oxen, and
wild goats, were found in a cave in Mount Langya in Yixian county.
</P>
<P>
Grey and yellow clay were found deposited at intervals in the
cave, suggesting an alternating of dry and rainy seasons.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts say that the find is a proof that the area used
to be warm and damp before the shift of a cold belt towards the
south tens of thousand years ago.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
