<HEADLINE> Fujian to Hold Festival for Sea Goddess </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, April 16 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian Province will
hold a festival to commemorate Mazhu, a sea goddess, in the coming
May.
</P>
<P>
A tourist trade fair with 153 projects will also be held during
the occasion.
</P>
<P>
Mazhu, a legendary figure from the Song Dynasty (960-1279)
believed to be a guardian of the sea, is worshiped in coastal
areas in the southeastern part of the country and in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the festival will be a rite to welcome the
return of a sculpture of Mazhu from Taiwan, which will be held in
Meizhou, hometown of Mazhu.
</P>
<P>
The sculpture, believed to be the body of Mazhu, was previously
enshrined in a temple in Meizhou. The sculpture was sent to be
worshipped in Taiwan earlier this year, for the first time in over
a millenium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
