<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diarrhea Hits Dhaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Diarrhea in Bangladesh's capital
city, Dhaka, has taken a serious turn over the last week with
about 600 diarrhea cases reported every day to the diarrhea
hospital in the city, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot term the present situation epidemic, but it is true
that the situation is serious," Dr. Iqbal Kabir, scientist of the
International Center for Diarrheal Disease Research, was quoted by
the English-language Independence as saying.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the spread of diarrhea to "contaminated" water
and was worried that the situation might get worse if adequate
steps were not taken to ensure the supply of pure drinking water
in the affected areas.
</P>
<P>
The hospital was overcrowded with diarrhea patients, most of
them children from the city's suburbs. During the last week, the
number of diarrhea patients was 550 to 600 everyday on the
average.
</P>
<P>
"The number of patients is larger compared to the same period
during last two years," Dr. Kabir said.
</P>
<P>
The center has a capacity for treatment of about 200 patients
in normal situation. Hospital authority had to increase the number
of beds to tackle the situation. Tents have also been set up for
accommodating the patients.
</P>
<P>
According to Dr. Kabir, the number of patients is likely to
rise in the coming months. "Normally in July and August the number
of patients increases. This year the number may increase further,"
he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
