<HEADLINE> Ramos Reiterates Decision to Step Down in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
reiterated today that he will definitely step down from office
when his term ends on June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
"My position is very clear and I've said it many times, I'll
graduate on the 30th of June 1998 from this office," Ramos said at
his weekly press conference.
</P>
<P>
The president was replying to a question that overseas
businessmen wanted him to run for a second term, which the
country's current constitution prohibits.
</P>
<P>
Foreign businessmen were reportedly worried that the political
and economic stability of the country might be affected if a new
government takes over.
</P>
<P>
Ramos has vowed repeatedly that he will not seek any
re-election. But his political critics are doubting this because
Ramos' supporters have been pushing for an amendment to the
charter to lift the term limit for all elective officials,
including Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Ramos ordered his ruling Lakas Party to
create a committee to recommend conditions for choosing his
successor. He is expected to soon anoint his successor, who will
run for the Lakas Party in the May 1998 general elections.
</P>
<P>
Among the possible presidential candidates in the
administration are Defense Secretary Renato de Villa, Speaker of
the House of Representatives Jose de Venecia, Finance Secretary
Roberto de Ocampo and Senator Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
