<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA, Israel Promise to Resume Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VALLETTA, MALTA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) and Israel today promised to return to
negotiation table after a direct high-level meeting brokered by
the European Union here.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between PNA President Yasser Arafat and Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy was held in a hotel outside the
capital of Malta under the presidency of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
This is the first direct official meeting between the two
sides since the Middle East peace process plunged to the worst
crisis in its seven-year history.
</P>
<P>
During the twenty-minute meeting, Arafat and Levy pledged
commitment to the peace process and returning to the
negotiations, said Arafat's spokesman Marnan Kanafani said after
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He described the meeting as a "good-will step" in pushing
ahead the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"There were warm and friendly exchanges of views" during
the meeting, he said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Levy expressed their appreciation to EU's efforts
in helping reactivate the stalled Middle East peace process, he
said.
</P>
<P>
An European Union (EU) source quoted Hans Van Mierlo,
foreign minister of the EU president, the Netherlands as saying
that the meeting will help "overcome the psychological obstacles"
in reviving the Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
Also present at Arafat-Levy meeting were PNA Minister of
Planning and International Cooperation Nabil Sha'ath,
European Middle East peace envoy Miquel Moratinos, French Foreign
Minister Herve de Charette and Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa, the source said.
</P>
<P>
Turning down reports saying that both Palestinian and Israeli
sides did not want to talk with each other despite EU
mediation, another EU source said they both expressed willingness
to talk but citing "usefulness" as the precondition.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries and the Palestinian National Authority have
suspended normalization process of their relations with Israel in
protest of Israeli hard-line policy in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The crisis, now coupled by daily stone-throwing incidents in
the West Bank, was triggered off with Israeli settlement policy
carried out a month ago in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Levy are attending the current
European-Mediterranean conference here, which devoted much of its
discussions to the impact of the faltering Middle East peace
process on the cooperation scheme between the two regions.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that Europe scored by successfully
brokering the Arafat-Levy meeting in its efforts to seek a
bigger role in the region aimed at counterbalance the United
States influence in the region.
</P>
<P>
The United States is the most important mediator in Middle
East peace. But its Israeli-biased stand costs Arab's trust in
it.
</P>
<P>
Both Arafat and Levy had separate meetings with EU
delegations at the conference last night. Earlier, they shook
hands with each other while taking a family photo of all the
participants of the conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference, the second of the type, is being attended
by the 15 EU members and their 12 Mediterranean neighbors,
which include all the major parties directly involved in the
Middle East peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
