<HEADLINE> Wool Market Set for Gradual Recovery in 1997-98: WI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Wool International (WI) today
released its first forecast for wool prices in 1997-98, saying it
expected a gradual but subdued recovery in the market.
</P>
<P>
WI, charged with selling off the wool stockpile, said
Australia's eastern market indicator was expected to average 630
Australian cents (491.5 U.S. cents) in 1997-98, plus or minus 100
Australian cents (78 U.S. cents).
</P>
<P>
WI also predicted that average wool price for 1996-97 would
remain unchanged at 600 Australian cents (468 U.S. cents) per
kilogram, assuming that prices would remain at the current level
during the final quarter of the season.
</P>
<P>
In its monthly insight newsletter, WI spokesman Bill Watkins
was quoted as saying, "WI expected some pick-up on the basis of
exports to China and others and economic recovery in Western
Europe."
</P>
<P>
Currently around 824,000 bales of wool is held in growers'
stocks, according to him.
</P>
<P>
Australia's chief commodities forecaster, the Australian Bureau
of Agricultural and Resource Economics, has earlier predicted an
average indicator price of 600 cents per kilogram this fiscal year
and 650 cents (20 cents more) per kilogram for 1997-98.  
</P>
</TEXT>
