<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi King Expresses Condolences Over Those Killed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The King of Saudi Arabia Fahd
Ibn Abdul-Aziz expressed condolence over the death of those
killed, at least 217, in the fire outside the Holy city of Mecca
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
King Fahd demanded that speedy aid be provided to the wounded
until their full recovery, Saudi Press Agency reports said..
</P>
<P>
A gas cylinder exploded Tuesday, setting some 70,000 tents
ablaze in the holy plain of Mena, a holy site of the the annual
pilgrimage Hajj in Saudi Arabia, some 11 kilometers outside Mecca.
</P>
<P>
The death toll of the fire rose to 217 pilgrims and 1290 were
wounded, according to latest official figures available here today.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait News Agency quoted a statement made by Director General
of the Saudi Civil Defense Department Mohammed Bin Ali Al-Sumaili
as saying that most of the casualties were caused by critical
injuries sustained by pilgrims as a result of the blazes.
</P>
<P>
He also said that scores of pilgrims were in critical
condition and are under treatment.
</P>
<P>
Prince Majed Bin Abdul-Aziz, the Amir of Mecca and Chairman
of the central Hajj Committee, has issued orders to the
authorities to provide tents and food for the ill-stricken
pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
A very tough job was started to clear the huge area hit by the
fire and to repair the damage inflicted to power sources, reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The fire stricken pilgrims had moved to Mount Arafat to
perform Hajj early this morning.
</P>
<P>
This is the latest tragedy to hit Hajj in Saudi Arabia
which had drawn about 2 million Muslim pilgrims from various
parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
The people who were killed in the fire were mainly Indians,
Pakistanis and Bangladeshis.
</P>
<P>
The annual Hajj has seen tragedies in recent years despite
Saudi Arabia made every possible efforts to ensure the safety for
the pilgrims and provide convenience to the pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
The worst of the recent Mecca tragedies was a stampede during
the 1990 Hajj in which 1426 pilgrims were crushed to death in a
tunnel.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, 270 pilgrims were killed during a stampede at
Mena. In March 1991 a plane crash in northern Saudi Arabia killed
91 Senegalese soldiers returning from a trip to Mecca. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
