<HEADLINE> S. African Bank Clerks Fearful of Armed Robberies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 16 (Xinhua) -- South African bank staff
are more afraid of armed robberies than retrenchment or any other
dangers, local daily "The Star" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The significant increase in the number of bank robberies has
caused great concern when more than 20 of Johannesburg's
financial institutions have been pillaged of more than five
million Rands (1.14 million U.S. Dollars) in the past month, said
Bob Tucker, chief chief executive officer of the Council of South
African Banks.
</P>
<P>
Both the public who make use of banking facilities and the
banking staff are desperately afraid, Tucker said, warning that
the cost may eventually have to be passed on to the consumer.
</P>
<P>
Tucker believed that more could be done to curb bank
robberies.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested the national bank system take more
tightening security measures, including the removal of firearms
from anyone entering a bank.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, South African Police Commissioner George Fivaz
declared armed robberies a national priority crime. 
</P>
