<HEADLINE> Denmark to Cut Aid to S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Demark is considering to
cut much of its foreign aid to South Africa next year in favor of
projects in other countries of the southern African region, a
local daily "The Citizen" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Danish Minister of Development and Cooperation Poul Nielson
was quoted by the report as saying in Cape Town on Tuesday that
Denmark, which committed about 112 million U.S. Dollars to South
Africa between 1994 and 1998, will thereafter give aid to more
challenging and difficult nations in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
However, Nielson said his country was very happy with how
South Africa had used Danish aid resources.
</P>
<P>
He said about one-third of the Danish aid package, including
joint ventures between Danish companies and their black South
African counterparts, will continue beyond the year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
He also reaffirmed that the Danish government will continue to
commit one percent of its annual gross domestic product to
foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a senior South African official thanked the Danish
government for the invaluable technical support, expertise and
funds given to South Africa, citing the planned aid cut is part
of a "normalization process" in relations between the two
countries. 
</P>
