<HEADLINE> Chengdu Becomes Trade &AMP; Commerce Center in Western China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, April 16 (Xinhua) -- This capital city of southwest
China's Sichuan Province has turned into the largest trade and
commercial center in underdeveloped western China thanks to
sustained rapid development in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the 1990s, the added-value of commerce
and trade in Chengdu increased at an annual rate of 20
percent. The percentage of service trade made up 42.1 percent of
the city's gross domestic product, higher than that of Beijing or
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Chengdu ranks third in the country in the number of commercial
centers and fourth place in the number of staff members working in
this sector.
</P>
<P>
He Shaohua, vice mayor of Chengdu, attributed the rapid growth
of commerce and trade to a great expansion of local markets in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
The local government has invested one billion yuan in building
745 new markets and 1,100 shops.
</P>
<P>
Chengdu has also become an exhibition center. The national
sugar fair was held in Chengdu for ten years in succession. A
number of economically-developed regions including Shanghai,
Jiangsu, and Guangdong have held exhibitions in the city, seeking
bilateral cooperation. 
</P>
