<P>
Jim Steer, director of DSA-Contact, a major human resource
consultants of the country, said on Tuesday that premiums of this
magnitude are paid only for experienced, top executives who have
proven abilities.
</P>
<P>
Steer said South Africa's business community was like a
village, the best, successful executive were well-known within
their respective industries and were frequently targeted by
head-hunters.
</P>
<P>
Companies wishing to recruit these "high-flyers" could expect
to pay a hefty premium to induce them to move from one top-level
position to another, particularly when they had to be compensated
for share options and incentives offered in their existing
positions, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, highly publicized salary packages paid to top
executives who were haed-hunted, would bear little resemblance to
market-related rates paid to executives with lower profiles or
new entrants to the top rank of executives, he added.
</P>
<P>
The size of South Africa's pool of top executives was believed
to have not increased over the past 15 years, except for the
addition of a small number of Black executives who were in more
demand than their white counterparts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
