<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Quarterly Tax Revenues Up 17.5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- China's industrial and commercial
tax revenues grew 17.5 percent on a yearly basis to 156.65 billion
yuan (about 18.87 billion US dollars) in the first quarter of this
year, according to the State Administration of Taxation (SAT).
</P>
<P>
That is an increase of 22.3 billion yuan over the same period
of last year, and 22.5 percent of this year's targeted figure.
</P>
<P>
Quarterly central tax revenues were 84.7 billion yuan, up 17.7
percent over a year ago, while local tax revenues rose 17.3
percent to 71.948 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Revenues from domestic value-added tax and the consumer tax,
two major items in China's new tax system introduced in 1994, were
up 17.2 percent on a yearly basis to 85.39 billion yuan in the
first three months.
</P>
<P>
The southern city of Shenzhen reported the largest increase in
industrial and commercial tax revenues for the period, followed by
Yunnan Province, the city of Qingdao, and Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
An SAT official said that there were still problems in the
collection of industrial and commercial taxes in the first three
months, and pointed to a resurgence in delayed tax payments,
stagnant growth in commercial tax revenues, and poor sales for
some enterprises that are major tax sources.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, industrial and commercial tax defaults
increased by more than 10 billion yuan during the period.
Value-added taxes from the commercial sector grew a mere 5.4
percent over a year ago to 18.42 billion yuan in the first three
months, with the rate much lower than that of retail sales during
the same period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Steps out to Control Risks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The China Construction Bank plans
to reform its outdated accounting and auditing system to deal with
the increasing number of financial risks.
</P>
<P>
Wang Qishan, the bank's president, said that the accounting and
auditing system still in use is not capable of meeting the bank's
growing needs for commercialization.
</P>
<P>
"In the absence of an advanced accounting or examination
system, commercial banks will be unable to expand their business,"
Wang noted in a speech at a meeting on accounting.
</P>
<P>
All the main state-owned banks in China began to turn
themselves into commercial banks several years ago to adapt to
tough market competition, but an effective accounting and auditing
system is yet to be introduced, and it is what commercial banks
need most, Wang noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that his bank will gradually separate these functions
of accountants from those of auditors. Previously accounting and
auditing were combined as one, and the bank will restrict the
power of presidents of its 45 branches at the provincial level to
extend loans.
</P>
<P>
The bank will also put a spending ceiling on each branch bank
at the county level, and keep a close watch on the performance of
each branch every year, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Home Car Market Up in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Boasting continued strong car
exports, the German Automobile Industry Association today reported
a upturn in Germany's domestic car market in March.
</P>
<P>
On a seasonally-adjusted basis, passenger car orders rose by 16
percent in March compared with that in February, and by nine
percent over a year earlier, said the association.
</P>
<P>
The car production last month totaled 343,000 units, down by
five percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the Frankfurt-based trade association said that the
output represented an actual five percent increase if taking the
factor of Easter Holiday weekend into account.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that 757,000 vehicles had been exported through
March this year, up three percent from the same period last year.
Passenger car exports increased by five percent in March on annual
basis, while commercial vehicles exports went up by 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the association, production through March totaled
1.24 million vehicles, down by four percent compared with those in
the first quarter of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
