<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 33 Civil Servants of S. Leone on Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, April 16 (Xinhua) - A total of 33 civil servants of
Sierra Leone, charged with corruption, appeared at a magistrate
court in capital Freetown today.
</P>
<P>
The accused, mainly middle-level accountants including seven
women, are from the ministries of health, fisheries and marine
resources and the treasury.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution, led by Attorney-General Solomon Berewa, said
the 33 people, 18 of whom are from the Health Ministry and the
Treasury, "falsified the government payroll to include people who
were not employed by the state and stole millions of Leones from
the state coffer from 1994 to 1996."
</P>
<P>
On the growing corruption in the civil service, Berewa said
the gap between revenue and expenditure has been growing over the
years.
</P>
<P>
"Part of this has to do with dishonesty by public officials
who operate within a complex conspiratorial web, particularly in
the Treasury," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Within the scheme, only a fraction of the revenue collected
on behalf of government by individuals was reported," said
Berewa.
</P>
<P>
"Ghost workers (non-existent workers whose names are still in
the state payroll) make the government keep paying huge sums into
the pockets of a few fraudulent individuals," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
