<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat, Levy Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VALLETTA (MALTA), April 16 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat and Israeli Foreign
Minister David Levy met and held talks here today.
</P>
<P>
This is the first direct official meeting between the two
sides since the Middle East peace process plunged to the worst
crisis in its seven-year history.
</P>
<P>
The meeting took place in a hotel outside the capital of Malta
under the presidency of the European Union and their talks
centered on the stalled Palestinian-Israeli peace talks, according
to sources of the Euro-Med Conference.
</P>
<P>
During the one-hour meeting, Arafat and Levy expressed their
appreciation to EU's efforts in helping reactivate the stalled
Middle East peace process, an European Union (EU) source said.
</P>
<P>
The sources quoted Hans Van Mierlo, foreign minister of the
EU president, the Netherlands as saying that the meeting will
help "overcome the psychological obstacles" in reviving the Middle
East peace.
</P>
<P>
Also present at Arafat-Levy meeting were European Middle East
peace envoy Miquel Moratinos, French Foreign Minister Herve de
Charette and Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
European Middle East peace envoy Miquel Moratinos is present at
the on-going meeting.
</P>
<P>
Turning down reports saying that both Palestinian and Israeli
sides did not want to talk with each other despite EU mediation,
the sources said they both expressed willingness to talk but
citing "usefulness" as the precondition.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries and the Palestinian National Authority have
suspended normalization process of their relations with Israel in
protest of Israeli hard-line policy in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The crisis, now coupled by daily stone-throwing incidents in
the West Bank, was triggered off with Israeli settlement policy
carried out a month ago in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Levy are attending the current
European-Mediterranean conference here, which devoted much of its
discussions to the impact of the faltering Middle East peace
process on the cooperation scheme between the two regions.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that Europe scored by successfully
brokering the Arafat-Levy meeting in its efforts to seek a bigger
role in the region aimed at counterbalance the United States
influence in the regin.
</P>
<P>
The United States is the most important mediator in Middle
East peace. But its Israeli-biased stand costs Arab's trust in
it.
</P>
<P>
Both Arafat and Levy had separate meetings with EU delegations
at the conference last night. Earlier, they shook hands with
each other while taking a family photo of all the participants of
the conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference, the second of the type, is being attended by
the 15 EU members and their 12 Mediterranean neighbors, which
include all the major parties directly involved in the Middle
East peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Northeast Chinese Market for Overseas Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- China's Jilin Province plans to
bring in four billion US dollars worth of investment from abroad
in the 1996-2000 period, a provincial government official said
here recently.
</P>
<P>
The figure is 45 percent more than for the previous five-year
period, he said, and 370 million US dollars will be used to import
advanced technology and equipment.
</P>
<P>
The import and export volume of the province is expected to
reach five billion US dollars by the year of 2000, and have an
annual increase of 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
Jilin has reported marked progress in foreign trade in the past
few years, with 2.6 billion US dollars worth of exports and
imports last year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, imports and exports as a percentage of
Jilin's GDP, had gone from 5.5 percent in 1990 to 16.3 percent,
and foreign exchange earned by overseas-funded firms from exports
made up 16.26 percent of the province's total.
</P>
<P>
A province-wide drive to readjust the export structure in
recent years has boosted exports of industrial products. The
number of types of manufactured goods for export has risen to over
1,000, and the export value of machinery and electronic products
was 180 million US dollars last year, triple the 1990 figure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
