<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Reviews Decree to Boost Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government is
planning a major review of the Nigerian Investment Promotion
Commission (NIPC) Decree 16 of 1995 in a bid to boost inflow of
direct foreign investment into the country.
</P>
<P>
The review is in consonance with the promise of Head of State
General Sani Abacha in this year's budget to abrogate all laws
inhibiting investments in key sectors of the national economy,
the Daily Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Despite the liberalization of the investment laws in recent
years, foreign investors are still reluctant to invest in the
non-oil sectors of the Africa's largest oil producing country,
due to various stringent procedures, especially in terms of
license registration.
</P>
<P>
The proposed amendment to the NIPC decree would ensure that
the power to register and license potential investors is vested
in the commission which is yet to be inaugurated, said the
national newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The government has set up a legal committee to examine other
laws which contain restrictions inhibiting competition in all
sectors of the economy.
</P>
<P>
The committee is expected to submit its report in the first
week of June to ensure the early take-off of the privatization
program of the government.
</P>
<P>
The NIPC decree, promulgated two years ago to replace the
abrogated Nigerian Enterprise Promotion Decree of 1989, has not
yet been effected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
