<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Company to Export Medicines to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has approved
two contracts for a Jordanian firm to supply Iraq with medicines
in line with the UN oil-for-food agreement with Iraq, the
Jordanian news agency Petra reported today.
</P>
<P>
Petra quoted Anis Muasher, chairman of the Arab Pharmaceutical
Manufacturing Co. (APMC), as saying that his company approved by
the Iraqi government, will dispatch the first shipment of
medicines to Baghdad in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The chairman added that the two contracts are part of the 26
deals, worth 20 million U.S. dollars, that the APMC has signed
with Baghdad. The remaining contracts will be approved soon, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The new approval brings to 13 companies the number of
Jordanian firms which received the U.N. permission to supply Iraq
with the humanitarian need.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the world body approved 11 contracts to supply the
sanction-hit country with 35 million dollars of detergents and
cooking oil.
</P>
<P>
At least 30 Jordanian firms are still awaiting to receive the
U.N. consent.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food accord Iraq is permitted to sell 2
billion dollars worth of oil, 1.3 billion dollars of which will be
funneled to Iraq to buy food and other necessities for its 19
million citizens.
</P>
<P>
Early this week, Iraq lashed out at the U.N. for being
responsible for the delayed delivery of medicines Iraq bought
under the agreement.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with U.N.-Iraqi agreement, Iraq gets
humanitarian purchases through the Jordanian port of Aqaba,
Iraqi port of Um Qasr and through Iraqi northern borders with
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has maintained its seven-year embargo on Iraq since
the Gulf War when the Iraqi troops were driven out of Kuwait
following its invasion of the oil-rich neighbor in August 1990.
</P>
<P>
Although official business exchange between Jordan and Iraq is
extremely difficult due to the U.N. embargo policy, unofficial
exchange seems to boom.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian and Iraqi businessmen on March 31 signed a
memorandum of understanding in Amman, which called for joint
ventures among businessmen in the two countries, exchange of
visits by trade delegations and holding trade fairs in their
respective capitals.
</P>
<P>
During the Gulf crisis, Jordan sided with Iraq but distanced
itself from Iraq after the war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
