<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Take Measures Against Shipping Accidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Marine Department
 will take a series of safety measures to forestall the
increasing accidents on the Hong Kong sea waters.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, 27 people were injured when a catamaran carrying
121 passengers and eight crew members collided with a car carrier
in western Hong Kong waters.
</P>
<P>
The collision caught the attention of the local communities and
the Marine Department which issued a warning for shipping
accidents.
</P>
<P>
According to the warning, booming port traffic could raise by
nearly half the annual number of marine accidents by the year 2011.
</P>
<P>
The department is stepping up policing and prosecutions among
the proposals outlined in conclusions from a two-year study on
making the territory's waterways safer.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by Au Posford consultants, forecasts a 43
percent rise in marine accidents -- from 223 in 1994 to 333 by
2011 -- unless urgent measures are taken.
</P>
<P>
Besides collisions, the study tackled incidents such as ships
running aground or catching fire.
</P>
<P>
The report recommended more government control over vessel
movements, enforced by prosecution if necessary.
</P>
<P>
It also suggested that the Marine Department boosts the number
of patrol crafts, provide more training for staff in the Vessel
Traffic Center and divert traffic from the most congested areas
and "black spots".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Plans To Counter Its Pollution Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 16 (Xinhua) -- This pollution-threatened
capital of south China's Guangdong Province has signed a contract
for a waste-water treatment system to purify 400,000 cubic meters
of effluent a day.
</P>
<P>
The Xilang Sewage Treatment System will be built in two steps
by the Lemna Co, a US firm, beginning sometime after June, said
today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
The system will help reduce water pollution along the Guangzhou
stretch of the Pearl River.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the new treatment system will cost 1 billion
yuan (120 million US dollars) and will be ready for use in the
year 2000. It will be able to cleanse 200,000 cubic meters of
waste water a day.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou's water supply facilities are often imperilled by
polluted water.
</P>
<P>
On March 20, 500 kg of heavy oil leaked into the Pearl River
300 m from the intake valve of the Baihedong water supply plant
when workers were unloading a Yuexing Shipping Co vessel in a
protected zone.
</P>
<P>
The plant was forced to cut off the water supply to residents
of the Fangcun district for more than three days as a precaution
against polluting their drinking water, said Tan Xiaomei, the
secretary of the water company.
</P>
<P>
"The incident, the most serious in the company's history,
caused enormous financial losses," Tan said.
</P>
<P>
Nor were the district's inhabitants happy.
</P>
<P>
"We did not receive any notice. The water was suddenly cut
off," said a Guangzhou Shipping Co official, who gave his name
only as Zeng.
</P>
<P>
He said the water company must improve its service.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
