<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal's Economy Expected to Grow 6 Percent Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's economy is expected to
grow 6 percent every year before 2000 after the country achieved a
moderate economic growth during the first half of the 1990s,
according to a survey released here today.
</P>
<P>
The Economic and Social Survey of Asia and the Pacific 1997,
prepared by the Bangkok-based Economic and Social Commission for
Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP), said Nepal's average annual growth
rate of gross domestic product (GDP) during the period from 1990
to 1995 was about 4.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, such a moderate economic growth left little room for
any perceptible rise in Nepal's per capita income, which stands at
around 210 U.S. dollars at present, mainly due to the over
2-percent population growth every year, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
A shining point in the generally gray picture of Nepal's
economy painted by the ESCAP survey is that the economic growth
was 6 percent last year after the government adopted liberal
economic policies to encourage private investment including
foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
It predicted that such a growth rate will be maintained in the
coming years.
</P>
<P>
But the survey also pointed out that like other least developed
countries, Nepal's high dependence on agriculture limited its
capacity to attract foreign investment and participate in
international trade.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, Nepal attracted some 8 million dollars
of foreign direct investment in 1995 and its trade deficit still
represented a high percentage of GDP in recent years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
