<HEADLINE> Northeastern Port City Using Foreign Funds for Retooling State-owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Dalian, a coastal city in
northeast China's Liaoning Province, has used more than 700
million US dollars from some 50 countries and regions to improve
technology and equipment in state-owned enterprises over the past
two years.
</P>
<P>
Local government has been encouraging state-owned firms to form
joint ventures for their land, workshops, and equipment. A Dalian
pen factory has spent 34 million yuan on a workshop and equipment
to form a joint venture with a Canadian firm that provided cash,
equipment, and technology.
</P>
<P>
Some of the better state-owned enterprises have opened
branches or trade offices in Southeast Asia and Europe. The
Bingshan (Iceberg) Group has set up 15 Sino-foreign joint
ventures, nine of which were built with the help of funds from
Japan's Sanyo.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, the amount of overseas investment
absorbed by local industrial enterprises accounted for a quarter
of that in the city last year. 
</P>
