<HEADLINE> Sanwa's Shanghai Branch Relocates to Pudong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai branch of the Sanwa
Bank Ltd. of Japan has relocated to the city's Pudong New Area to
qualify for business in the Chinese currency.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese bank, one of eight overseas banks approved by the
People's Bank of China, the country's central bank, to deal in the
local Renminbi yuan, has moved to the 16th floor of the Shipping
Building.
</P>
<P>
Sanwa Shanghai will start the yuan-based business after passing
the examination by the Chinese central bank on the hardware it
uses, said Yoshiaki Kawamata, the branch president.
</P>
<P>
"We need to learn from our Chinese counterpart, as yuan-based
business is an entirely new field to us," he told Xinhua, adding
that he is confident in the prospects of the new business.
</P>
<P>
China's central bank has approved two groups of eight overseas
banks to deal in the yuan on a trial basis in Shanghai's Pudong
New Area, a financial and trade district separated from downtown
Shanghai by the Huangpu River.
</P>
<P>
As a qualification for the new business, the overseas banks
must move their Shanghai branch to Pudong, though they are allowed
to retain a sub-branch in the downtown areas.
</P>
<P>
The overseas banks can accept yuan deposits from the
overseas-funded enterprises registered in Shanghai and from
overseas individuals, and they can extend yuan loans to
Shanghai-based overseas-funded enterprises and to state-owned
Chinese enterprises, according to rules set by the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Sanwa's Shanghai branch was set up in May 1991 and has since
participated in a number of syndicated loans to China's major
construction projects. The Japanese bank has another two branches
in China, in southern Shenzhen City and northeastern Dalian City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
