<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Shuts Down Nuke Power Reactor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 16 (Xinhua) -- A tritium leakage has prompted
Japan's Power and Nuclear Fuel Development Corporation (Donen) to
shut down an advanced thermal reactor, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Donen's delayed report on the accident has angered Japan's
Science and Technology Agency, which ordered the shutdown of the
Fugen reactor in Tsuruga, Fukui Prefecture, on late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The tritium leakage is the third accident to have occurred at
the Donen's plants in less than one and a half years.
</P>
<P>
Sodium coolant leaked in December 1995 at the Monju prototype
fastbreeder reactor in Tsuruga, and an explosion happened in March
this year at a bituminization facility at the nuclear fuel
reprocessing plant in Tokaimura, Ibaraki Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Fugen, the only heavy water reactor among the 50 nuclear
reactors now in use in Japan, started operation in 1979 with an
annual capacity of 165,000 kilowatt-hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
