<HEADLINE> China to Send All Top Players in Defence of Sudirman Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese shuttlers, fresh from
their historic victory in the All-England championships, are
confident to retain the title in the Sudirman Cup World Badminton
Mixed Team Championships, which are scheduled in Glasgow, Britain,
on May 19.
</P>
<P>
They also eye for at least two titles in the 10th World
Championships following the team event.
</P>
<P>
Looking through the name lists of the 28 Glasgow-abound
players, no one has the doubt that these are only the odd dreams.
</P>
<P>
Olympic runner-up Dong Jiong and Sun Jun, ranked first and
second in the world, have the calibre for a big shot in the men's
singles.
</P>
<P>
Both have showed their top form last month by securing the top
two places in the men's singles in the All-England championships,
in which China bagged four out of the five titles on offer.
</P>
<P>
Women's world number one Ye Zhaoying, a member of the winning
team in the Sudirman Cup and singles title holder two years ago,
has regained her prowess again after a disppointing slump in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The 23-year-old Ye breezed past compatriot Gong Zhichao, now
ranked second in the world, to win the women's singles in the
All-England tourney.
</P>
<P>
The world top two shuttlers are sure to launch a two-pronged
thrust at the women's singles.
</P>
<P>
World top duo Ge Fei and Gu Jun, who won the gold medal in the
Atlanta Olympic Games, are also favorites for the women's doubles.
</P>
<P>
China is also believed to be strong enough in the mixed doubles
event as the mixed tandem Liu Yong and Ge Fei boasted of their
unbeaten slate in 1997 by winning all the titles in their four
outings.
</P>
<P>
Men's doubles event is the only weak link for the Chinese
team. But after a hard training session, Ge Cheng and Tao
Xiaoqiang, Liu Yong and Zhang Wei are capable of staging serious
threat to any pairs in the upcoming tournament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
