<HEADLINE> Explosion Occurs Before Greek Troops' Departure for Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 16 (Xinhua) -- An explosion on a train in the
suburb of Aghioi Anargyri, west of Athens, damaged two army
vehicles today just before the first company of 120 Greek soldiers
were expected to leave for Albania later in the day.
</P>
<P>
So far, there have been no reports of injuries.
</P>
<P>
The home-made device went off at 1:45 a.m. local time as the
train carriage loaded with army vehicles was parking at the
railway station facing the 301 "Koskina" military camp at Aghioi
Anargyri, the police said.
</P>
<P>
The device was placed under one of the vehicles, which,
according to unconfirmed reports, were destined for Albania.
</P>
<P>
However, Greek Defense Ministry sources confirmed that two
other small explosions also occurred near an army camp, causing
slight damage to military trucks on a train platform.
</P>
<P>
Greece has decided to send troops to participate in the
Italian-led multinational force to Albania for securing the
delivery of humanitarian assistance there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
