<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Economy Grows in Northwest Chinese Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Privately-run enterprises and
individual household-operated firms contributed 12.5 billion yuan
to the economy of northwest China's Gansu Province last year,
emerging as a major force in local economic development.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 830,000 people from about 400,000 enterprises and
households are engaged in the sector, accounting for 5.6 percent
of the province's total labor force, the provincial Administration
Bureau for Industry and Commerce said.
</P>
<P>
The province abolished some regulations that hindered the
growth of the private sector, and reduced the number of fee
charges from the original more than 200 to 33.
</P>
<P>
Those private enterprises and individuals that concealed their
identities, fearing they might be charged excessive fees at
random, are requested to make themselves known to fairly compete
in the market.
</P>
<P>
The Linxia Hui Autonomous Prefecture took the lead in
developing its private economy, aimed at helping the needy shake
off poverty. The local government encouraged its poor population
to go outside the mountainous areas and engage in transporting
goods for sale. One third of the farmers in the prefecture were
able to increase their income as a result.
</P>
<P>
The registered capital of the province's private sector has
amounted to 5.03 billion yuan, and more investment has gone into
primary and secondary industries, the bureau said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
