<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suzhou Works to Control Pollution in Taihu Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Residents of Suzhou city in east
China's Jiangsu Province are now getting higher-quality drinking
water from the newly-purified Taihu Lake.
</P>
<P>
Taihu is the third largest freshwater lake in China, covering
an area of more than 2,300 sq. kilometers, about 80 percent of
which is in the province.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent survey, the lake's water quality is in
line with the state criteria for Category II water.
</P>
<P>
Over the past decade, Taihu's water quality has dropped to the
third category as a result of heavy pollution, and the lake was
listed as a key national pollution control project.
</P>
<P>
To decontaminate the lake, the city government launched a
"Clean Water" project last year, which led to the closing of more
than 190 enterprises which were sources of pollution. In addition,
regulations were formulated to ban any new enterprises expected to
be excessive polluters.
</P>
<P>
Under the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000), the city will
invest 770 million yuan (about 93 million US dollars) in
pollution-control, and one billion yuan (about 120 million US
dollars) in the comprehensive treatment of the water environment.
</P>
<P>
In Wujiang, a county-level city known for its silk printing and
dyeing industry, no more printing and dyeing projects will be
approved, some illegal mills for wool sweater printing and dyeing
were closed, and some projects which caused heavy pollution were
ordered to stop production.
</P>
<P>
Run-off of fertilizer and pesticide from the farmland is
another major cause of lake pollution. The city has built pilot
scientific farming areas along the waterfront to teach farmers how
to till Farmland with less pollution and higher yield.
</P>
<P>
Suzhou invested 45 million yuan (about 5.4 million US dollars)
in sewage treatment last year, dredging 35 kilometers of river
along part of the city area.
</P>
<P>
Four sewage treatment plants, able to treat a total of 130,000
tons of sewage each day, have been built in the city, raising the
sewage treatment rate to ten percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aquatic Products Transaction Growing Rapidly in Chinese Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- China's total output of aquatic
products is expected to increase at a double-digit rate to reach
31 million tons this year.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the figure topped 28 million tons, up 11.2 percent
from the previous year, lastest statistics from the Fishery Bureau
of the Ministry of Agriculture show.
</P>
<P>
The demand for aquatic products is bound to increase, as
China's rural and urban residents both have more and more income,
ministry authorities note.
</P>
<P>
However, they point out that the supply and demand of aquatic
products are not balanced in all regions, owing to the limitations
of frozen, processing, and transport conditions, and the Chinese
market's lack of high-grade aquatic products.
</P>
<P>
Generally, the business grew very quickly. Statistics show that
the transaction volume of aquatic products stood at 10.15 million
tons last year, with a value of 113.5 billion yuan, up 20.8 and
30.5 percent, respectively, over 1995.
</P>
<P>
Though the price index of aquatic products rose by six percent
last year, the growth rate was 8.4 percentage points lower than
1995. In addition, the increase was 8.6 percent in the first half
of 1996, and only 3.5 percent in the latter half. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
