<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Rural Residents in Henan Use Clean Toilets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, April 16 (Xinhua) -- More than 6.8 million farmers,
or 36 percent of the rural households, in central China's Henan
Province have replaced traditional dry latrines with flush
toilets, improving environment to a great extent.
</P>
<P>
Chinese environmentalists deem it a "revolution" in rural
China. For centuries, the old-style latrine was an earthen pit
with two boards on each side. it gave off a foul odor and
attracted swarms of flies.
</P>
<P>
In 1987, a farmer named Song Lexin, in Yucheng County of Henan,
invented a new-style toilet complete with jars underneath the
seat, a cover on the top and a flush system.
</P>
<P>
Since then, he travelled around the country by bicycle to
persuade the fellow countrymen to try his new design.
</P>
<P>
The new toilet is clean, odorless, cost-efficient and more
likely to prevent spread of disease than the traditional model. In
addition, the fermented soil can be used on grain crops, and is
said to be able to raise the output 20 percent, Song said.
</P>
<P>
Song's toilet has become widespread in Henan since 1989. The
provincial government plans to transform all the rural latrines in
the coming years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
