<HEADLINE> Roux to Face Becker in Japan Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Lionel Roux of France struggled to
eliminate compatriot Jean-Philippe Fleurian 7-6 (7-3), 6-4 on
Wednesday, setting up a third-round clash against Boris Becker in
the one million U.S. dollar Japan Open tennis tournament.
</P>
<P>
The 16th seed Roux broke Fleurian's serve to take the lead in
both sets, but each time Fleurian fought back playing some
aggressive chip-and-charge tactics.
</P>
<P>
Becker, three-time Wimbledon champion from Germany, needed
three sets to beat Canadian Sebastien Lareau on Tuesday in his
first match after a two-month layoff due to an injury to his right
wrist.
</P>
<P>
In other second round action, Australia's Patrick Rafter and
doubles spcialist Mark Woodforde swept to straight-set victories.
</P>
<P>
Sixth-seeded Rafter breezed past Eyal Ran of Israel 6-0, 6-4,
while Woodforde brushed aside Martin Sinner of Germany 6-1, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
American Jeff Tarango defeated Japan's Takao Suzuki 6-3, 6-2,
and his compatriot Jonathan Stark edged past Frederik Fetterlein
of Denmark 4-6, 6-3, 7-5, while fifth-seeded Thomas Johansson of
Sweden brushed aside Daniel Nestor of Canada 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Shuzo Matsuoka became the only Japanese left in the men's
action after beating compatriot Hideki Kaneko 7-5, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
In the women's case, Amy Frazier of the United States advanced
to the quarter-finals by beating Japan's Yuka Yoshida 6-4, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Wang Shi-ting of Chinese Taipei, and Annabel Ellwood of
Australia also joined Frazier in the the quarter-finals. 
</P>
