<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Total Closure on West Bank Reimposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Israel reimposed overnight a
total closure on the West Bank amid warnings of new terror
attacks against Israeli targets.
</P>
<P>
The order to impose the indefinite closure, which became
effective at midnight last night, was issued by Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai and Army Chief of Staff Amnon Lipkin Shahak.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security officials said they had concrete warnings of
terrorist attacks by Palestinian militants.
</P>
<P>
Under the closure, all Palestinians from the West Bank are
barred from entering Israel and the Jewish settlements in the West
bank, while Israelis are banned from entering areas under
Palestinian control. Unlike in the past, the closure does not
affect the Gaza Strip and Palestinian workers coming from there
are still being allowed in to seek jobs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli army restricted the rule of hitchhikes by
soldiers, who are easy targets of terrorist attacks and
kidnapings. According to the new rules, soldiers traveling
between 6 a.m. to 7 p.m. must hitchhike in pairs, and after 7
p.m., they must be armed. Female soldier is only allowed to
hitchhike when accompanied by a male soldier, and forbidden to
hitchhike at night.
</P>
<P>
Closure of the territories is a common practice adopted by
Israeli government at every time when there is a warning of
terrorist attacks. The Palestinians slammed the practice as a form
of collective punishment.
</P>
<P>
Israel imposed a full closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip
on March 21 immediately after a suicide bomber from the militant
Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) blew himself up at a Tel Aviv
cafe, killing three Israeli women and wounding 40 others. The
closure barred tens of thousands of Palestinian workers from
entering Israel to return to their jobs.
</P>
<P>
But Israel significantly eased the closure in the past days,
allowing over 20,000 Palestinians workers to enter Israel to
work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moi Criticizes West Nations Over Double Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
said Kenya is dismayed by western countries' move to impose
export quotas on the products from developing countries and to
provide subsidies to their own exports.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the developed countries of using double
standards to push for economic liberalization, saying that their
protectionist practices are unfair and constrain economic growth
in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Opening a four-day exhibition on Tuesday organized by the
British government, Moi stressed that trade liberalization could
only remain permanent and rewarding if all nations liberalize
trade.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan leader pointed out that the developed world has
been at the forefront in calling for global liberalization and
should therefore be the last ones to engage in protectionism.
</P>
<P>
He noted that east African countries have come together under
the auspices of the East African Co-operation to remove trade
barriers. 
</P>
