<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polluter Shut-down Influences Economy Very Little: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The director of China's State
Bureau of Environmental Protection said here today that the
country's large-scale polluter shut-down has had very little
impact on the overall regional economy.
</P>
<P>
Xie Zhenhua told Xinhua News Agency that the regional economy
has witnessed only about one percent change as a result of the
move.
</P>
<P>
Ninety percent of the factories' employees are farmers and
migrant workers, he noted, adding that they have been helped to
find jobs elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Xie said that the shut-down is meant to develop the economy
while saving resources and energy. It is conducive to the healthy
growth of the rural economy and ecological protection, he said,
adding that it also helps factories choose the "right way" for
development.
</P>
<P>
Such a large-scale move is rare in the world, Xie said, and
many developed countries are unable to do it, let alone other
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"This shows China's determination in environmental protection,"
Xie stressed.
</P>
<P>
China has shut down 62,561 factories causing serious pollution,
according to the lastest official statistics. Those closed so far
include paper mills with an annual production of less than 5,000
tons, tanneries producing less than 30,000 pieces of cow leather,
coking plants using outdated production processes, and other
factories causing serious pollution.
</P>
<P>
The action came following last year's decree of the State
Council, China's highest governing body, that required all the
country's 15 types of small-sized factories causing serious
pollution to close their doors.
</P>
<P>
These polluters have seriously affected the country's economic
development and barred the improvement of the living environment.
</P>
<P>
Sources with the bureau said that the bureau and the Ministry
of Supervision will inspect the country's 17 province-level areas
on their implementation of the council's decree, and prevent the
closed factories from resuming operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
