<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Mobile Telecom Networks to Adopt CDMA Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The rapidly growing Chinese
mobile telecommunications industry is now importing the latest
wireless technology - CDMA (code diversion mode accesses) standard
- to ease the pressure created by the swelling market on the
present infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Li Xiuchuan, vice director of the Mobile Telecom Bureau under
the Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications, said that the
country's mobile telephone subscription has reported a growth rate
of 120 percent over the past few years, and there will be as many
as 18 million clients in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
However, the radio frequency range suitable for mobile phone
use is very limited, Li pointed out.
</P>
<P>
To meet the ever-growing market demand, "the only way out is to
develop a technology that can make more use of radio frequencies,"
Li said.
</P>
<P>
China is now building several trial CDMA networks in such
populous cities as Guangzhou, Beijing and Shanghai. The handling
capacity of the CDMA networks is reported to be ten times higher
than the present analog mobile telecom standard.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of Lucent Technologies, one of the global
telecom giants leading the CDMA trend, in Beijing said that China
dialed the first CDMA call on the trial network launched by Lucent
Technologies in Guangzhou on December 31, 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Lucent network with a switching capacity of 20,000 accesses
will undergo its final test by the end of this month, and will go
into formal operation next month. It will be the first commercial
CDMA system operational in China.
</P>
<P>
Wang Quan, manager of wireless network unit of Lucent
Technologies (China) Ltd., said that China, as the fastest-growing
market in the Asia and Pacific Region, and in which the company
has won CDMA contracts of 250 million US dollars, is now
technically qualified to adopt the CDMA technology countrywide.
</P>
<P>
Motorola, another major CDMA supplier from the US, is also
accelerating the construction work on two trial networks in
Beijing and Fujian Province. It made the first CDMA call in
Beijing early this month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, other CDMA manufacturers, including Nortel of Canada
and Samsung of South Korea, are eagerly waiting to enter the
Chinese marketplace.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that once the country decides to open the market to
foreign CDMA suppliers, the telecom administrative body will
encourage the foreign companies to make technical transfer.
</P>
<P>
"China has always adhered to the principle of trading market
for technology. Therefore, the earlier the CDMA technology is
transferred, the easier it will be for the company to make its way
into the Chinese market," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
