<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Benefit From Grain Storage Organization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese farmers in disaster areas
are getting adequate food supplies thanks to relief grain storage
societies that have been emerging in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The grass-roots organizations were begun by civil affairs
departments to help alleviate the governments' burden by helping
farmers cope with periods of shortages.
</P>
<P>
Villages and townships are responsible for putting aside a part
of farmers' surplus grain and for doling out relief supplies to
the needy, for free, or by borrowing or selling at a discount.
</P>
<P>
Haidong Prefecture in northwest China's Qinghai Province is a
major grain producer for the province, but has long been plagued
by natural disasters, causing more than 100,000 people to run
short of grain annually, said Ba Mingwang, director of the
prefecture's Civil Affairs Department.
</P>
<P>
So, the department encouraged farmers in poor villages and
townships to set up mutual aid and relief societies in 1994,
asking farmers to set aside surplus grain on their own. Societies
have been set up in 104 of the prefecture's 150 townships, and
more than 200,000 households have joined, accounting for nearly 60
percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
The societies had over four million kg of grain in storage and
handed out 3.5 million kg to the needy last year, effectively
regulating the grain supply in disaster areas.
</P>
<P>
This practice has been welcomed by rural Chinese homes, because
grain stored this way can keep its value and save farmers the
trouble of storing too much grain at home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three-Fold Increase in Number of Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The number of Chinese cities has
tripled since 1980, to 666, according to the latest statistics
from the Chinese Ministry of Construction.
</P>
<P>
A senior official with the ministry told Xinhua today that
China's urbanization is characterized by growth in medium-sized
and small cities, and an increasing number of cities in central
and western parts of China.
</P>
<P>
The country's urbanization strategy aims at "controlling the
number and scale of large and extra-large cities and to give
greater room to medium-sized and small cities as well as small
rural towns," he noted, adding that it has begun to pay off.
</P>
<P>
Of these 666, extra-large and large cities account for 75,
medium-sized cities, 192, and small cities, 399.
</P>
<P>
The official said that because of economic development
nationwide, the rapid pace of urbanization has improved the uneven
distribution of cities in eastern, central, and western parts of
the country to some degree. These three areas now account for 44
percent, 37 percent, and 19 percent, respectively, of the total
number of cities.
</P>
<P>
The autonomous regions of Inner Mongolia, Xinjiang and Ningxia
and the provinces of Hubei, Qinghai, Shanxi, Anhui, Henan and
Jiangxi are seeing faster urbanization than the rest of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The number of cities is expected to reach 800 by the turn of
the century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
