<HEADLINE> Abductees Return to Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Thirty women abducted by rebels
have returned to western Uganda, "The New Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The women, part of 350 women and children abducted when ADF
rebels invaded western Uganda on November 13 last year, escaped
earlier this month from a camp overrun by Zairean Banyamulenge
rebels in Bukira, eastern Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The exhausted women spent eight days on the 50-km route. They
said the food store of the ADF rebels was destroyed in the
battle.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Peter Kerim, commander of the second division of the
Ugandan government troops, said the women will be handed over to
local authorities after proper questioning.
</P>
<P>
In the northern district of Kitgum, the Ugandan army rescued
22 civilians abducted by the LRA rebels, James Oryem Canogura,
assistant resident district commissioner, was quoted by the
newspaper as saying. 
</P>
