<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coastal Area of South China Improves Transport Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIHAI, April 16 (Xinhua) -- China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region has begun to develop transport facilities in the Beibu Gulf
area to provide clear access to the sea for the Nanning-Kunming
railway line, a new transport artery in China's vast southwestern
region, linking the Yunnan-Guizhou plateau with the gulf area.
</P>
<P>
Beihai, Qinzhou and Fangcheng are the three main ports in the
area. In recent years, Guangxi has spent nearly one billion yuan
on transport and telecommunications between them and Nanning, the
regional capital and the eastern end of the 898-km Nanning-Kunming
railway line.
</P>
<P>
The capacity of railway lines between the three ports and
Nanning is 10.25 million tons annually, enough to meet the cargo
demands of the Nanning-Kunming railway for now.
</P>
<P>
Work on an expressway from Nanning to Beihai, a section of the
Chongqing-Beihai expressway to be completed before the end of
2000, has begun, and the Qinzhou-Fangcheng expressway is scheduled
to be open this year. So, an expressway network connecting Nanning
with the three ports is expected to be completed by 1998.
</P>
<P>
The three ports have 15 deep-water berths, handling more than
13 million tons of cargo each year, and port authorities are
renovating and improving warehouses, and loading and unloading
facilities to cope with the expected influx of cargo from the
railway.
</P>
<P>
Twelve more deep-water berths will be built in the three ports
by the end of the century. Construction of two has begun already
at Fangcheng port. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
