<HEADLINE> Roundup: Chinese NPC Leader Concludes European-Asian Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the Standing
Committee of the Chinese National People's Congress (NPC) Qiao Shi
today concluded his European-Asian tour, which took him to France,
Norway, Italy and Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time a top Chinese NPC leader had visited
the four countries.
</P>
<P>
During his three-week trip, Qiao met with heads of state,
parliamentary leaders and prime ministers, as well as other senior
officials, and exchanged views with them on bilateral relations
and issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
He said China attaches great importance to developing
cooperation with the four countries in politics, the economy,
trade, culture and other fields.
</P>
<P>
China is willing to further cooperation with these countries on
the basis of mutual respect, equality and mutual benefit, and
together with them, to establish long-term, stable cooperative
relations geared towards the 21st century, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said China was also willing to enhance friendly and
good-neighborly relations with Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the four countries said that China, as a permanent
member of the United Nations Security Council, was an important
factor for world stability and played an influential role in
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
They believed it was very important for their countries to
better relations with China, as China was one of the prosperous
markets in the world.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the three European nations reaffirmed their support
for China's efforts to enter the World Trade Organization, while
Mongolian leaders said Mongolia would continue to maintain
long-term, friendly and good-neighborly relations with China.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, France and Italy informed him that they would
not raise anti-China resolution at the United Nations Conference
on Human Rights in Geneva. Qiao expressed his appreciation for
their action and reaffirmed China's stand on the human rights
issue.
</P>
<P>
On the Hong Kong issue, Qiao stressed that China would adhere
to the policy of "one country, two systems" and implement
conscientiously the Basic Law (of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China), so as to
ensure that the region would enjoy a high degree of autonomy and
maintain long-term prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the three European countries agreed that it was
important to maintain Hong Kong's prosperity and stability. They
said they believed the Chinese government could deal with the
problems which would emerge after it resumed the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Qiao also told these leaders that China would continue
unswervingly along the road, blazed by the late Chinese leader
Deng Xiaoping, of building socialism with Chinese
characteristics. It would strive to push ahead with the
modernization drive by deepening reform and opening wider to the
outside world.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the Chinese NPC leader's four-nation
European-Asian tour had enhanced mutually-beneficial cooperation
between China and European countries, as well as friendly and
good-neighborly ties between China and Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
Qiao's visits had further strengthened exchanges and
cooperation between the Chinese NPC and parliaments of these four
countries, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
