<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugabe Challenges African Health Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe has urged Africa's health professionals to come together
and help fight mounting challenges posed by diseases and
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
At the fifth international congress of the Association of
Medical Laboratory Scientists of South-Central and Southern
Africa held in Harare on Tuesday, Mugabe said there is a need for
medical facilities to be accessed by the majority of the people.
</P>
<P>
"The challenges for health have never been greater because in
the field of human development, ill health, diseases and
disability have all been recognized as retarding factors in that
process, especially in the African context," he said.
</P>
<P>
The congress is being attended by top African scientists from
all over the continent.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe asked the laboratory technologists to strive for higher
goals by producing quality scientific results to help establish
proper patient diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
Africa, he said, faces serious problems in its continuing
efforts to control infectious diseases, both old and new.
</P>
<P>
"Recent experience with TB, malaria and AIDS indicates that
political, social and economic considerations will increasingly
dictate priorities," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
