<HEADLINE> National Park's Elephants Play Havoc With Villages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The increasing number of wild
elephants in a national park of West Nepal have reduced the
presence of other wildlife in the park and created difficulties
for villagers living nearby, a local newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
The Bardia National Park, about 400 kilometers southwest of
Kathmandu, used to have some 70 tigers but the number of visible
tigers has decreased sharply due to the havoc wreaked by the
elephants, the Kathmandu Post reported.
</P>
<P>
The elephants, numbering 45, have also spread chaos in nearby
villages by destroying trees, plantation and crops.
</P>
<P>
Local inhabitants urged the park authorities to take urgent
measures to stop further damage to crops by the elephants and
protect the villagers from losing their livelihood.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, the Nepali government and the World
Wildlife Fund (WWF) have initiated measures to grant relief to the
people living around the nearly 1,000-square-kilometer park, which
also has a buffer zone of 460 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The measures include uplifting the living standard of the
villagers and preventing wild animals from leaving the park by
digging trenches around the park.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
