<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Joins World Submarine Cable Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's semi-private
telecommunications company Pt. Indosat has begun operating three
newly completed submarine optic fiber cable systems worth a total
of 1.8 trillion rupiah (783 million U.S. dollars), an official
said.
</P>
<P>
Janathan L. Parapak, secretary general of the Tourism, Post and
Telecommunications Ministry, said here Tuesday that the three new
systems, which began operation on Monday, are the Jakarta-Surabaya
(East Java) submarine optic fiber cable system (J-S), the Asia
Pacific cable network (APCN) and the Jakarta-Australia submarine
optic fiber cable system (JASURAUS).
</P>
<P>
The J-S system, with a distance of 715 kilometers, had been
built by Alcatel Submarine Network (ASN) since May 1995 with an
investment of 115 billion rupiah (50 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The APCN, covering a distance of 12,082 kilometers, was jointly
built by 56 telecommunications operators form 27 countries. Its
cable terminals are located in Jakarta, Singapore, Malaysia,
Thailand, the Philippines, Hong Kong, Taiwan, Japan and South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
The APCN system, which is connected with Southeast Asia, the
Middle East and Western Europe, was built with a total investment
of 1.45 trillion rupiah (602.5 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The JASURAUS system was built by Telstra and Optus Australia
with a total investment of 156.9 million Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The three cable systems use a technology called "synchronous
digital hierarchies" (SDH) with a large transmission capacity,
which is able to transmit 60,480 telephone lines simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
"These three cable systems have made Jakarta a hub of the
global information network linking Western Europe, the Middle
East, Australia, Asia-Pacific and America," Indosat President
Director Tjahyono Soerjodibroto said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
