<HEADLINE> UNFPA Provides Aid for Sri Lanka's Health Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will receive from the
U.N. Fund for Population Activities (UNFPA) 7.6 million U.S.
dollars in support of a reproductive health program in the
country, according to official sources today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the program will help Sri Lanka shift from
family planning to reproductive health.
</P>
<P>
The program proposes the setting up of 300 "Well Women's
Clinics" specially in difficult areas and vulnerable groups such
as estate workers, free trade zone workers and displaced people,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Mobile services are also envisaged for displaced people.
</P>
<P>
The sources said a newly-established Non-Governmental
Organization Secretariat will act as the implementing agency for
the program.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that an integrated project of
reproductive health services is undertaken in Sri Lanka.
</P>
</TEXT>
