<HEADLINE> Taliban Commander Captured by Opposition Faction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 16 (Xinhua) -- A top commander of the Afghan
Taliban militia has been captured by an anti-Taliban faction in
the fighting which broke out three days ago, a local newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Wahid, the Taliban commander in charge of the frontiers
75 kilometers northwest of the capital of Kabul, was taken
prisoner by Hezb-e-Wahdat, an Afghan Shiite Muslim faction which
is a main part of the country's anti-Taliban alliance.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, about 60 Taliban soldiers have been captured and
dozens killed in the fighting, the report quoted a general of the
faction as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Hezb-e-Wahdat general, Bashir Tawhidi, said the Taliban had
attacked the faction's positions in the Ghorband Valley which is
seen as a "backdoor" to the north for the Taliban to conquer the
remaining one-third of the country.
</P>
<P>
But the attack was repulsed, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, which seized Kabul on September 27 last year,
control two-thirds of Afghan territory.  
</P>
</TEXT>
