<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO, Russia Hold Talks on Eastward Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 15 (Xinhua) -- North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) Secretary General Javier Solana met Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov here today for the fourth round of
secret talks about future relations between Moscow and the Western
alliance after it expands eastward.
</P>
<P>
After three hours of talks, the Russian side came out with a
brief statement which said that a planned pact on future relations
was far from ready, and consultations between the two sides would
continue.
</P>
<P>
The two sides came nearer on a series of issues but still had
some problems that must be solved, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
A senior official from the Russia's State Duma (the lower house
of parliament) said today that the current trip of Solana to
Moscow was aimed at discussing some details of the document
governing Russia-NATO relations in future, including NATO's use of
military facilities of the former Warsaw Pact bloc and deployment
of armed forces on soil of its new member countries.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said last week that Russia hoped to sign a partnership
document with NATO on May 27 in Paris.
</P>
<P>
But Russian President Boris Yeltsin said, in an interview with
the German magazine Stern today, that Moscow would not sign such a
document unless the results of the talks suited Russia.
</P>
<P>
Russia fears that the Western alliance's plans to invite in
former Soviet bloc countries in July would lead to a military
build-up near its borders. Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic
are the front-runners to join NATO.
</P>
<P>
Russia is also demanding a role in NATO decision-making,
complaining that some NATO members were not showing enough desire
to seek a compromise.
</P>
<P>
Solana left Moscow immediately after the end of today's talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Presidency Agrees On Unified Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Bosnian presidency Tuesday
agreed on the circulation of a unified currency known as
"convertible mark" in the country.
</P>
<P>
The currency with a one-on-one rate with German mark is likely
to be issued within 100 days, said Mirza Hajric, an advisor to the
chairman of the presidency, Alija Izetbegovic.
</P>
<P>
Hajric said that the currency will be temporarily circulated
for one year until "some technical problems" about a permanent
banknote are sorted out.
</P>
<P>
For the present, the three ethnic groups in Bosnia use three
different currencies with Bosnian Dinar for Muslims, Yugoslav
Dinar for Serbs and Croatian Kuna for Croats.
</P>
<P>
The use of a single currency in the country is one of the
requirements set by the international community for holding a
conference on financial assistance to Bosnia this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
