<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Naval Ships Join Russian Manoeuvre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 15 (Xinhua) -- For the first time since the
division of the former Soviet Union's Black Sea Fleet, the
Ukrainian Naval ships today joined a Russian-sponsored manoeuvre.
</P>
<P>
Two Ukrainian ships left the Sevastopol base today to
participate in the exercise and will act as observers when the
Russian fleet reachs the navy port of Kerch.
</P>
<P>
The manoeuvre, involving 50 vessels, marine corps, naval air
force, ground rocket artillery force, will carry out over 160
combat programs, under the direction of Viktor Klavchenko,
commander of the Russian Black Sea Fleet.
</P>
<P>
The large-scale manoeuvre is seen as a show of force against a
proposed multinational manoeuvre on the Black Sea to be
participated by NATO countries in August.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the navy before the manoeuvre, Klavchenko said
that Russia's southwestern part is of great military importance in
view that the forces of the non-Black-Sea countries are becoming
increasingly active with NATO's eastwards expansion nearing the
border of Russia.
</P>
<P>
The Black Sea Fleet was divided between Russia and Ukraine in
August 1992, but the two countries still keep a joint fleet
headquarters to carry out manoeuvres. 
</P>
</TEXT>
