<HEADLINE> Thailand's Economic Crime Rate Up in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's economic crime rate
increased 25 percent last year from the year before, according to
the Economic Crime Investigation Division.
</P>
<P>
A total of 3,604 cases were reported to the division last year,
compared with 2,700 cases in 1995, the Nation today quotes Somboon
Kachornsarnsit, spokesman of the division, as saying.
</P>
<P>
As a result, business damages totaled 27 billion baht (1.08
billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said 2,809 suspects were arrested in connection with the
cases that were forwarded to the division.
</P>
<P>
The cases included 71 cases of fraud relating to banks and
financial institutions totaling 4 billion baht (160 million
dollars) and 79 cases of credit card fraud worth 1.65 billion baht
(66 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said there were also 475 cases involved the smuggling of
contraband goods totaling 3.44 billion baht (137.6 million
dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
