<HEADLINE> Russian Pipeline to Go Through Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Russia and Bulgaria will further
their cooperation by laying a natural gas pipeline from Russia to
the Balkans through Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
A joint communique on the scheme was signed today by Russian
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and his visiting Bulgarian
counterpart, Stefan Sofianski.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Bulgaria agreed in principle to allow Russia to lay
the pipeline which would cost 600 million U.S. dollars. In return,
Russia agreed to continue its supply of oil and natural gas to
Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
The Inter-fax news agency said the signing of the communique
guaranteed the transit of natural gas from Russia to the Balkans,
and free trade between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two prime ministers also exchanged views
on bilateral trade and some international issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin told reporters that both sides reached common
understanding on many issues and Russia would further its
cooperation with Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
Russia's supply of Mig-29 jet fighters to Bulgaria was also
discussed, and the text of the agreement on this was nearly
finalized, he noted.
</P>
<P>
But Bulgaria would like to further study this military
contract, he added.
</P>
<P>
On the North Atlantic Treaty Organization's eastward expansion,
the Russian prime minister pointed out that Russia respected
Bulgaria's stand in hoping to join NATO, but did not support the
idea.
</P>
<P>
Russia would not forsake its principle of opposing NATO's
eastward expansion, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
