<HEADLINE> Philippines Launches Campaign Against Polio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- An estimated 9 to 10 million
children will flock to medical centers all over the Philippines
today for polio immunization as the first round of this year's
massive campaign against the disease unfolds in the country.
</P>
<P>
An official report from the Department of Health showed that
the polio virus was last isolated from a case in the southern city
of Cebu in 1993. Since then, there was no reported polio case due
to wild poliomyelitis virus.
</P>
<P>
But the health authorities said that the Philippines still can
not be certified polio-free because the country's active acute
flaccid (AFP) paralysis surveillance failed to meet basic
requirements and standards.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the polio disease is eradicated in the country, the
health authorities decided to regularly launch a massive Knock Out
Polio Campaign nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country will take measures to improve its AFP
surveillance system, which reportedly lags very much among the
countries and regions in the Western Pacific.  
</P>
</TEXT>
