<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (25-26)
in a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: Can holders of the British Dependent Territories
Citizens (BDTC) and British Nationals Overseas (BNO) passports
continue to use these passports and travel outside Hong Kong after
1997?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Since Hong Kong returns to China on July 1, 1997, the
BDTC passports will be valid only until June 30, 1997. The Chinese
Memorandum attached to the Sino-British Joint Declaration states,
"Taking account of the historical background of Hong Kong and its
realities, the competent authorities of the Government of the
People's Republic of China will, with effect from July 1, 1997,
permit Chinese nationals in Hong Kong who were previously
called 'British Dependent Territories Citizens' to use travel
documents issued by the Government of the United Kingdom for the
purpose of travelling to other states and regions."
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law also clearly stipulates that Hong Kong residents
have the freedom to travel and to enter or leave the
region. Unless restrained by law, holders of valid travel
documents will be free to leave the region without special
authorization.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, holders of the BDTC passports can apply for BNO
passports currently issued by the British Government, and continue
to use BNO passports to travel after 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, holders of BNO passports will not be entitled to
British consular protection in the Hong Kong SAR and other parts
of China on account of their holding the above-mentioned British
travel documents.
</P>
<P>
Question: Will Hong Kong residents have freedom of movement?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Article 31 of the Basic Law stipulates that Hong Kong
residents have freedom of movement within the Hong Kong SAR and
freedom of emigration to other countries or regions. They will
also have freedom to travel and to enter or leave the region.
</P>
<P>
Unless restrained by law, holders of valid travel documents
will be free to leave the region without special authorization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
