<HEADLINE> Nicaraguan President Asks FSLN to Act in Civic Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Nicaraguan President Arnoldo
Aleman today asked the Sandinista National Liberation Front (FSLN)
to act in a civic way, saying that "Nicaragua will be the only
loser" of the protest marches that are being carried out in the
country.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview, the president said that he has
instructed the police to remain calm and avoid using force except
for protecting the rights of citizens' freedom of movement.
</P>
<P>
The nationwide protest against government policy promoted by
FSLN yesterday has seen its first negative fruit of higher prices
for most important agricultural staples resulted from roadblocks
against international transportation.
</P>
<P>
Answering Sandinista leader Daniel Ortega's proposal for a
dialogue between the government and the FSLN with the
participation of the international community, Aleman said that the
Nicaraguans "are grown up now." "Our domestic problems should be
solved by the Nicaraguans," he added.
</P>
<P>
"We don't need to call on other countries when we can solve our
problems among Nicaraguans with good will," Aleman said, adding
the transition period of his country "is behind us and there is a
need to institutionalize democracy through laws."
</P>
<P>
"The forums for debate are the national forums decided upon by
the people, such as the National Assembly, and for that reason I am
calling on the Sandinista Front to make a change for Nicaragua
without violence," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
