<HEADLINE> Italian Senate Calls for End to Iraqi Embargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Italian Senate approved a motion
today calling for the lifting of the international economic
embargo on Iraq, and the release of frozen Iraqi assets.
</P>
<P>
The motion, still waiting for the ratification of the Chamber
of Deputies (lower house), demanded the government push for an end
to the embargo, imposed by the United Nations after Iraq's
invasion into Kuwait in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The motion also requires the Italian government to make efforts
to persuade the international community to release Iraqi assets,
frozen in Italian and other foreign banks, and use them to provide
food and medicine for the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
The senate also approved another motion calling on the Italian
government to support some non-governmental organizations, which
are working to safeguard the civil rights of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Senators from both government and opposition parties voted for
the two motions, with abstentions only by senators from the
separatist Northern League party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
