<HEADLINE> Aoyama's World Record Ratified </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The swimming's world governing
body has ratified a short-course world record in the women's
100-meter butterfly set in Tokyo last month.
</P>
<P>
Ayari Aoyama of Japan clocked 58.24 seconds on March 28 to beat
the 58.29 set by American Misty Hyman in Quebec City on December 1
last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, FINA declined to acknowledge another new time set by
Ryan Mitchell of Australia in the men's 200 meters short-course
breaststroke.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell clocked two minutes 7.66 seconds to better the 2:07.80
set by fellow Phil Rogers on August 28, 1993.
</P>
<P>
But FINA refused to ratify the new time because Mitchell set it
in a time-trial arranged for him after he had been disqualified
for an incorrect touch in the heats and ruled out of the final.
</P>
</TEXT>
