<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FM Spokesman on Foiling Anti-China Draft Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government today
expressed its admiration and gratitude to all the countries that
have upheld justice and rendered support to China in foiling for
the seventh time an anti-China draft resolution proposed by some
Western countries.
</P>
<P>
China also expressed its hope that the US, Denmark and a few
other countries that have clung to a confrontational approach will
seriously consider the call of the international community for
cooperation and against confrontation, draw a lesson from their
failure and make a clear break from their erroneous practice of
tabling an anti-China draft resolution.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Shen Guofang made the
remarks here today after some Western countries' attempt to pass
an anti-China resolution at the UN Human Rights Commission session
was foiled for the seventh time.
</P>
<P>
On the evening of April 15, Geneva time, the Commission on
Human Rights of the United Nations decided, with 27 votes in
favor, 17 votes against and 9 votes in abstention, not to take
action on the so-called "Situation of Human Rights in China" draft
resolution co-sponsored by the US, Denmark and a few other Western
countries.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the Chinese government has all along
attached importance to the issue of human rights, and made
unremitting efforts and scored enormous achievements in promoting
the civil, political, economic, social and cultural rights of the
Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
"However, the US, Denmark and a couple of other Western
countries have, in total disregard of facts, obstinately clung to
their position of politicizing the human rights question, and
attempted to use the Human Rights Commission session to table an
anti-China draft resolution, in a bid to put pressure on China,
interfere its internal affairs, undermine its stability and
obstruct its development and progress," Shen said.
</P>
<P>
As such a practice runs counter to the fundamental principles
of the UN Charter, it has naturally met with the opposition of the
majority members of the UN Human Rights Commission, Shen noted.
</P>
<P>
"China has always stood for resolving differences between
countries on human rights through dialogues on an equal footing,
and against creating a political confrontation over it," he
stated. "China is heartened to note that a considerable number of
Western countries have stayed away from cosponsoring this year's
anti-China draft resolution while expressing the will to resolve
their differences on human rights with the Chinese side through
dialogues and cooperation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
