<HEADLINE> Canadian Women Remain Unbeaten in Curling World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Skip Sandra Schmirler led her rink
to an 8-4 victory over Scotland Tuesday, extending Canada's
winning streak to five straight games at the World Curling
Championships in Bern, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian women have geared up for their third title in five
years after victories in 1993 and 1994, although Jan Betker pulled
out a second time with a strained thigh muscle.
</P>
<P>
Led by Patti Lank, the United States chalked up a 9-8 win over
Denmark, their second victory of the competition.
</P>
<P>
In other games, Japan defeated Finland 7-4, Sweden beat
Norway 9-7 and Germany breezed past Switzerland 7-6.
</P>
<P>
In the men's actions, both Canada and Denmark suffered their
first losses of the tournament, but kept their place atop the
standings with 5-1.
</P>
<P>
Denmark defeated Canada 8-6 before a 5-3 loss to Scotland in
the sixth round, and Canada came back to nip Switzerland 7-4.
</P>
<P>
The United States slowly clawed its way back into contention,
with a 6-5 win over Norway and an 8-6 victory over Germany in the
fifth and sixth rounds for a 3-3 record. 
</P>
</TEXT>
