<HEADLINE> Argentina Vows to Combat Money Laundering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Argentine government
today reaffirmed its commitment to fight the laundering of
drug-related money.
</P>
<P>
Opening an international meeting on money laundering here,
Interior Minister Carlos Corach warned about the
"transnationalization" of money laundering.
</P>
<P>
He said that the issue had formed part of the permanent agenda
of the South American Common Market (Mercosur), the regional trade
bloc.
</P>
<P>
The International Congress on Money Laundering, co-sponsored by
the United States Financial Crimes Enforcement Network and
Interpol, aimed at detecting and preventing money laundering
through analyzing bank transactions and reports.
</P>
<P>
Corach said that at a recent meeting of the central banks of
the Mercosur, which groups Brazil, Argentina, Uruguay, Paraguay
and Bolivia, a draft agreement was drawn up on collaboration in
the war against money laundering.
</P>
<P>
He called for globalization of standards, and information and
technology to meet the challenge of the "globalization of crime".
</P>
</TEXT>
