<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay's Banco Republica Oriental (BROU, its
acronym in Spanish) has just dropped its interest rate on consumer
credit in national currency by 8 percent to 79 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
This is the second reduction so far this year after interest
rates were lowered 2 percent on March 15 from 89 to 87 percent.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rican coffee exports reached 67.94 million
U.S. dollars during the first 2 months of this year, an increase
of 2.6 percent compared with the same period last year, according
to Foreign Trade Ministry statistics.
</P>
<P>
Overseas coffee sales made by this Central American country
reached 35.33 million dollars in January and 32.61 million in
February.
</P>
<P>
Local economists attributed this increase mainly to the high
prices of coffee beans in the international market in the past
few months.
</P>
<P>
Coffee is one of Costa Rica's principal traditional export
products. In 1996 the total value of coffee exports reached
378.55 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Panama's banana exports reported a drop of
810,000 boxes (18.4 kilograms per box) during the first quarter of
1997 with a reduction of 9.3 percent in volume, compared with the
same period in 1996, informed Euclides Diaz, director of the
Commerce and Industry Ministry's National Banana Commission.
</P>
<P>
As of March 31, 1997, Panama had exported 7,884,000 boxes of
bananas, which was inferior to the 8,694,000 exported in the
previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
In the Pacific region, and more specifically, in Puerto
Armuelles, the decrease was 20 percent while the drop in the
Atlantic region was 9.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's non-traditional exports amounted to
5.1 billion dollars in 1996 which accounted for 33 percent of its
total shipments which totalled 15.394 billion dollars, informed
Prochile, the Chilean Foreign Ministry department in charge of
promoting exports.
</P>
<P>
Chilean wines headed the list of non-traditional exports in
1996 with a total of 187 million dollars equal to 4 percent of
non-traditional exports and 1.2 percent of total Chilean exports.
Furthermore exports of juice powders, noodles and services showed
growth.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Coca cola de Colombia, S.A., one of the
companies through which the U.S. multinational operates in
Colombia, obtained a profit of 20.666 billion pesos (close to 20
million dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the balance sheets of the Bogota Chamber of
Commerce and a Confecamaras publication, Coca Cola sales
rose from 60.450 billion pesos in 1995 to 71.423 billion last
year.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- In 1996 Mexico's paper production reached a
volume of 3.162 million tons, an increase of 3.8 percent
compared with 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to data supplied by the National Chamber of Pulp
and Paper Industries, paper imports in 1996 increased 86,000
tons over 1995, a figure that represents an increase of 13.3
percent. (to be continued)

nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
