<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA -- The Nicaraguan-Guatemalan Chamber of Commerce,
Industry and Tourism was installed in the capital with a
ceremony held last weekend which was attended by Nicaraguan
Foreign Minister Emilio Alvarez and his Guatemalan counterpart
Eduardo Stein.
</P>
<P>
The Guatemalan minister estimated that there are some 20
companies in his country that are investing individually or in
joint-ventures in Nicargua and pointed out that this chamber is an
example of the entrepreneurial exercise that allows us to think
that Central America is approaching integration ideals.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Industrial output increased by about 5 percent
in March compared with the same month last year, according to
estimates by specialists based on Economy Ministry figures.
</P>
<P>
The most outstanding increases in March corresponded to the
cement industry with 27.7 percent, automobile production with
26.4 percent, steel 3.9 percent and aluminum with 34.1
percent, all compared with the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuela's economy grew one percent during the
first quarter of this year, exactly as projected by the national
government.
</P>
<P>
On making an evaluation of the implementation of the economic
program, Finance Minister Luis Raul Matos Azocar admitted to the
existence of several "red spots" such as not having reached real
positive interest rates but he was optimistic and highlighted
the "cualitative achievements" that can be seen in the return of
investor confidence and in the fact that Venezuelans are beginning
to save in bolivars, Venezuela's national currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
