<HEADLINE> More People to Surf Internet for Purchasing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 15 (Xinhua) -- More than 10 million people will
regularly make purchasing on Internet by the year 2000, according
to a survey by a U.S. research group recently.
</P>
<P>
"We are about to experience a fundamental change in marketing
and in how we approach the Internet," said J. Neil Weintraut,
founder of the 21st Century Internet Partners.
</P>
<P>
The on-line marketplace recorded 300 million U.S. dollars in
commerce in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The survey involving 100 of the nation's foremost marketing,
advertising and media experts, who met recently to debate the
future of on-line commerce.
</P>
<P>
While 22 percent of survey respondents felt Internet commerce
would become a profitable industry by 2000, 43 percent felt
Internet commerce would not be a profitable business for most
companies until after the turn of the century. Marketers and
advertisers are trying to decide how and when their investment in
new media will pay off.
</P>
<P>
The experts polled all agreed that there are still serious
barriers to the Web becoming a mature retail medium.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four percent of respondents who thought the most serious
barrier was that many products cannot be fully experienced on the
Web. Other barriers noted included the difficulty of using the Web
for purchasing transactions, and the perception by consumers of a
lack of "iron clad" credit card security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Confrontation on Human Rights Unpopular </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The 53rd session of the United
Nations Commission on Human Rights today approved China's
preemptive no action motion, thus defeating the attempts of the
United States, Denmark and some other Western countries to seek
confrontation in the Human Rights Commission and to interfere in
China's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The approval of China's no action motion means that the
commission will not vote on a draft resolution on China's human
rights practices concocted by the United States, Denmark and some
other Western countries.
</P>
<P>
As an old Chinese saying goes, "Thrice is the maximum." Before
today's failure, the United States had for six consecutive years
instigated and supported certain countries to table and try to
push through anti-China resolutions in the Human Rights
Commission. And every time, its efforts were foiled because of the
opposition of the majority of the commission's members.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, the United States, Denmark and some other
Western countries refused to learn from the previous
embarrassments and was unwilling to end confrontation with
China. They resorted to double-dealing this time: on one hand,
they claimed that they favored dialogue, but on the other hand,
they made confrontations by insisting on a new anti-China
resolution.
</P>
<P>
The move of these countries naturally met opposition from the
majority of the commission's members.
</P>
<P>
Facts prove that confrontation on human rights is not popular.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese people care most about their human rights and they
are best qualified to speak on this matter.
</P>
<P>
Before the founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949,
the Chinese people, oppressed by imperialism, feudalism and
bureaucrat-capitalism, enjoyed no human rights at all. After the
founding of the People's Republic, the Chinese people completely
shattered off the chains of oppression and became masters of their
country and the human rights situation in China was fundamentally
improved.
</P>
<P>
Since China began its policy of reform and opening up to the
outside world in the late 1970s, China focused its attention to
economic development and at the same time, improved its democracy
and legal system. With less than 7 percent of the world's arable
land, China feeds 22 percent of the world's population and has
significantly improved their economic, social, cultural, civil and
political rights.
</P>
<P>
In the meanwhile, China takes an active part in U.N. activities
promoting and protecting human rights. It has signed 17
international conventions on human rights and announced that it
will sign "the International Covenant on Economic, Social and
Cultural Rights" before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
At present, China enjoys political stability, economic growth,
social progress and ethnic unity and the living standards of the
Chinese people are increasingly rising. Its human rights conditions
have kept a good momentum of continuous improvement.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the New York Times, J. Stapleton Roy,
former U.S. ambassador to China, said current human rights
conditions in China are the best in the past 100 years. Based on
their own experiences in China, former U.S. President George Bush
and a Ford Foundation representative in China said that most
Chinese people now enjoy unprecedented human rights and freedom.
</P>
<P>
Totally disregarding those facts, repeated vetos by the
U.N. Commission on Human Rights and even the announcements by some
Western states not to participate in drafting anti-China
resolutions, the United States and a few other nations insisted on
having their own way and tabled a seventh draft resolution against
China.
</P>
<P>
What calls for deeper thought is that the years during which
they kept tabling anti-China drafts were exactly the ones during
which China registered fast economy growth and all-round human
rights progress.
</P>
<P>
The countries sponsoring anti-China drafts in the U.N.
Commission on Human Rights are the nations which once invaded
China and wantonly trampled on the human rights of the Chinese
people. It is obvious that the United States and a handful of
Western states have ulterior motives in making a fuss about the
so-called China human rights issue year after year.
</P>
<P>
To put it bluntly, they want to see neither China's pursuing of
an independent and peaceful foreign policy and sticking to the
development road of building socialism with Chinese
characteristics, nor its development into a powerful nation and
the real improvement of its human rights conditions.
</P>
<P>
However, they made a miscalculation. China, with 5,000 years of
civilization, is a country full of vitality and hopes. The 1.2
billion Chinese people, who have stood up and are making strides
forward, will never yield to alien pressure and change their road
of development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EMI Unsatisfied With EU States' Marks to Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Monetary Institute
(EMI) today said it is generally unsatisfied with the European
Union (EU) states' performance to meet the qualification
requirements for the planned single European currency.
</P>
<P>
The EMI also urged these states to adopt even stricter
budgetary discipline.
</P>
<P>
In its annual report for 1996 released today, the
Frankfurt-based EMI, the forerunner of the planned European
central bank, noted that there had been some progress toward
curbing inflation, achieving exchange rate stability and
harmonizing long-term interest rates.
</P>
<P>
But the situation in many EU states still remained very
unsatisfactory with regard to budget deficits, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficits of most of the EU countries remained above
the limit of 3.0 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP)
required by the Maastricht Treaty for qualifying for the common
currency called the Euro, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The EMI also voiced concern over another key Euro target which
requires a member state to trim its national debt to no more than
60 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that despite favorable developments in some
countries, it had registered an overall rise in EU states'
national debts.
</P>
<P>
Luxembourg still remained the only country so far to meet all
the five Euro criteria, the EMI said.
</P>
<P>
The EU is targeting to launch the Euro on January 1, 1999.
Decision on which countries will be able to make the first wave to
join the Euro is expected to be made in May 1998, based on full
economic data of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The EMI report said despite of growing concern over whether the
Euro could be launched on time, the preparations were going ahead.
</P>
<P>
The first designs of the Euro notes unveiled late last year are
being revised at the moment, after which, production of the
printing plates for the notes would get underway, the EMI said.
</P>
<P>
The Euro notes are due to formally enter into circulation by
January 1, 2002 at the latest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC Invests in Jordan's Tourism Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) today announced the approval of a loan of up to
15 million U.S. dollars and an equity investment of up to 3
million dollars in Jordan's tourism sector.
</P>
<P>
The investment for Zara, a tourism company in Jordan, will be
utilized to develop two hotel-and-business complexes in Amman and
the Dead Sea.
</P>
<P>
The projects will comply fully with the World Bank
environmental guidelines, the IFC said. This is particularly
critical for the Dead Sea project which will serve as a model for
future tourism projects.
</P>
<P>
IFC is a member of the World Bank Group and the largest
multilateral source of equity and loan financing for the private
sector in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, IFC has invested 186 million dollars, including 70
million dollars for the account of participants and 116 million
dollars for its own account, in 10 projects in Jordan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
