<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Confrontation on Human Rights Unpopular </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As every one knows, the U.S. is not a country with glorious
human rights record. It has serious human rights abuses, such as
deep-rooted racial discrimination, money-bag democracy, violence
and terrorism, wide-spread drug abuses and AIDS, increasing
single-parent families, the homeless, discrimination against
women, neglect of children and infringement upon other
countries' human rights.
</P>
<P>
Ironically, when the U.S. was trying to exert pressure on China
under the pretext of human rights at the 53rd session of the
U.N. Commission on Human Rights in late March, a human rights
abuse incident occurred in the U.S. where it was not accidental. A
13-year-old black boy was badly beaten up in Chicago by three
young white men who were actuated by racial hatred.
</P>
<P>
In a broadcast speech following the accident on March 29,
President Bill Clinton admitted that racism is a "constant curse"
in the nation and African Americans and other ethnic minorities
have to endure racial discrimination in their daily life.
</P>
<P>
What right has the United States, a country with such a bad
human rights record, to play the role of "world human rights
judge"?
</P>
<P>
Instead of examining its own mistakes, the U.S. persists in
slashing other countries' human rights records and instigating
resolutions against other countries in the U.N. Human Rights
Commission. What is this if it is not typical double standard?
</P>
<P>
The anti-China resolution initiated by the United States and a
small group of western countries was once again defeated at the
current session of the U.N. Commission on Human rights. The fact
shows that confrontation on human rights is a dead end and
cooperation and dialogue are the only choice.
</P>
<P>
This year's session of the U.N. Human Rights Commission is
characterized by growing calls from developing countries for
cooperation and non-confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen developing countries, including China, have put
forward a draft resolution calling for cooperation, dialogue and
consultation.
</P>
<P>
More and more developing countries voiced their criticism over
the practices of some Western countries to politicalize the human
rights issue and take the advantage of the session to engage in
political confrontation and adopt double standards. They strongly
called for cooperation instead of confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Western countries such as France, Germany, Italy,
Spain, Greece, Japan, Australia and Canada announced that they
would not co-sponsor anti-China resolution and advocated that
constructive dialogues should replace confrontation at the
U.N. session on human rights.
</P>
<P>
The stance of these countries shows that more and more
countries come to recognize that to create confrontation by
presenting country resolutions in the Human Rights Commission have
come to a dead end.
</P>
<P>
We advice the U.S. and a small group of other Western countries
to abandon confrontation and move towards cooperation.
</P>
<P>
China is willing to join hands with other countries in the
world to continue to safeguard the principles of the U.N. Charter,
to promote international dialogues and exchanges in the field of
human rights and to push the development of human rights on
healthy track. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
