<DOCNO> XIE19970416.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Defends No-Action Motion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- China's chief of delegation to the
53rd session of the U.N. Commission on Human Rights, Wu Jianmin,
today defended China's no-action motion on a draft resolution by
some 15 Western countries led by the United States.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the session, Wu outlined the reasons why China
proposed that the commission take no action on the draft
resolution against China.
</P>
<P>
"It is sheer demagogy to claim that the no-action motion proposed
by the Chinese delegation is asking for special treatment and
non-cooperation," said Wu. "China has always adopted an attitude of
cooperation with the UN human rights bodies. It has never proposed a
no-consideration motion. The no-action motion proposed by the Chinese
delegation in the past years was to counter those anti-China draft
resolutions."
</P>
<P>
He called the allegation that the no-action motion asked for
special treatment "totally groundless." "The no-action motion is
clearly provided for in the Rules of Procedure. It is not an
invention by China," Wu said.
</P>
<P>
"Anyone with common sense knows that in the meetings of many
other UN bodies, no-action motion is resorted to in accordance
with the Rules of Procedure," he explained.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that the draft resolution was a gross
distortion of China's reality designed to assert that China had a
deplorable human rights record.
</P>
<P>
Wu urged those countries bent on tabling the anti-China draft
resolution to return to the path of dialogue and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In a vote by the 53 commission members today, China's no-action
motion was approved 27-17, with nine abstentions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
